context_en: Portugal has the most liberal laws regarding possession of illegal drugs in the Western world. context_en: All objects from everyday life that we can bump into, touch or squeeze are made of atoms. This atomic matter in turn interacts with subatomic particles – typically a nucleus of protons and neutrons, and a cloud of electrons. Generally, science considers these composite particulate matter because they have both rest mass and volume. In contrast, massive particles such as photons are not considered matter, because they have neither rest mass nor volume. However, all particles with rest mass have classical quantities, because fundamental particles such as quarks and leptons (sometimes equated with matter) are considered "point particles", with no effective size or volume. Nevertheless, quarks and leptons together form "normal matter", and their interactions contribute to the effective amount of the overall particles that make up normal matter.

context_en: Predatory lending refers to the practice of unscrupulous lenders enticing borrowers to enter into "unsecured" or "unsound" secured loans for inappropriate purposes. Such loans were written into massively detailed contracts, and were swapped for more expensive loan products on the day of closing. While the advertisement may say that 1% or 1.5% interest will be charged, the consumer will be put into an adjustable rate mortgage (ARM) in which the interest payments will exceed the amount of interest. This created negative amortization, which the credit consumer may not notice until the loan transaction is completed.

context_en: Matter typically exists in four states (or phases): solid, liquid and gas, and plasma. A focus on the elementary-particle view of matter also leads to new phases of matter, such as quark–gluon plasma. For most of the history of the natural sciences people have pondered the precise nature of matter. The idea that matter was composed of discrete building blocks, the so-called particle theory, was first put forward by the Greek philosophers Leucippus (~490 BC) and Democritus (~470–380 BC).

Yutaka Tanaka, who suggests that the gravitational constant disagrees with experimental findings, proposes that Einstein's work does not actually refute Whitehead's formulation. Whitehead's view has now been rendered obsolete with the discovery of gravitational waves. Those phenomena have been observed locally that violate the local flatness of large-scale space that Whitehead assumes. As a result, Whitehead's universe should be treated as a local conjecture, and his notion of a similar spatio-temporal geometry, the Minkoloskian, should often be treated as a locally-sufficient conjecture. An accurate replacement of Whitehead's cosmology would require accepting Riemannian geometry. Furthermore, although Whitehead himself gave only secondary consideration to quantum theory, the metaphysics of processes has proven attractive to some physicists in that field. Henry Stapp and David Boehm are among those whose work has been influenced by Whitehead.
questions_en: What effect did the discovery of gravitational waves have on Whitehead's theory?
answers_en: Whitehead's view is now rendered obsolete with the discovery of gravitational waves.

context_en: The X3.2 subcommittee designed ASCII based on the earlier teleprinter encoding system. Like other character encodings, ASCII specifies a correspondence between digital bit patterns and character symbols (i). graphemes and control characters). It allows digital devices to communicate with each other and to process, store, and communicate character-oriented information such as written language. Before ASCII was developed, encodings in use included 26 alphabetical characters, 10 numeric digits, and 11 to 25 special graphic symbols. To incorporate all of these, and to control the letters compatible with the Comité Internationale Téléphonique et Telegraphique (CCITT), the Interurban Telegraph Alphabet numbers. 2 (ITA2) standard, FieldData, and early EBCDIC, ASCII required more than 64 codes.
questions_en: How much code was required for ASCII?

context_en: Armenian literature dates back to 400 AD, when Mesop Mashtots invented the first Armenian alphabet. This period is often seen as the Golden Age of Armenian literature. Early Armenian literature was written by the "Father of Armenian History", Moses of Korin, who wrote a history of Armenia. The book covers the time-frame from the formation of the Armenian people to the fifth century AD. There is a great literary movement in the nineteenth century which was to give rise to modern Armenian literature. This period of time, during which Armenian culture flourished, is known as the Revival Period (Zartanki Sherchan). The revivalist writers of Constantinople and Tiflis, almost identical to the Romantics of Europe, were interested in encouraging Armenian nationalism. Most of them adopted newly created Eastern or Western forms of the Armenian language, depending on the target audience, and preferred them over Classical Armenian (Grabar). This period ended after the Hamidian Genocide, when the Armenians experienced turbulent times. As the 1920s and the Armenian history of the genocide became more openly discussed, writers such as Periyar Sevak, Gevork Emin, Silva Kaputikyan and Hovhannes Shiraz began a new era of literature.

context_en: Infrared cleaning is a technique used by some motion picture film scanners, film scanners and flatbed scanners to reduce or remove dust and scratches on the finished scan. context_en: Since life began on Earth, five major mass extinctions and several minor events have led to large and sudden drops in biodiversity. The Phanerozoic Eon (the last 540 million years) saw a rapid increase in biodiversity through the Cambrian explosion – a period during which the majority of paleontology first appeared. Repeated over the next 400 million years, massive biodiversity losses classified as mass extinction events occurred. In Carbonfarmer, rainforest collapse caused a major loss of plant and animal life. The worst was the Permian–Triassic extinction event 251 million years ago; vertebrate recovery took 30 million years. The most recent, the Cretaceous–Paleogene extinction event, occurred 65 million years ago and often receives more attention than others because it resulted in the extinction of the dinosaurs.

context_en: According to R. Rummel, genocide has 3 different meanings. The general meaning is the killing by the government of people because of their national, ethnic, racial, or religious group membership. The legal meaning of genocide refers to the international treaty, the Convention on the Prevention and Punishment of the Crime of Genocide. It also includes non-killings that ultimately destroy the group, such as preventing births or forcibly transferring children from one group to another. A generalized meaning of genocide is similar to the ordinary meaning, but also includes government killings or otherwise deliberate killing of political opponents. To avoid confusion about what this means, Rummel created the term democide for the third meaning.
questions_en: In Rummy's writings, what is the first and general meaning of genocide?

context_en: The Treaty of Hubertusburg between Austria, Prussia and Saxony was signed on February 15, 1763, at a hunting lodge between Freudensburg and Leipzig. Negotiations began on December 31, 1762. Frederick, who had considered ceding East Prussia to Russia if Peter III helped secure Saxony, ultimately insisted on excluding Russia (in effect, no longer a rebel) from the negotiations. At the same time, he refused to evacuate Saxony unless its electorate renounced any claims to reparations. The Austrians wanted to retain at least the glazes that they had actually renovated, but Frederick would not allow this. The treaty merely restored the situation of 1748, with Silesia and Glatz to Frederick and Saxony to its own electorate. The only concession that Prussia made to Austria was consent to the election of Archduke Joseph as Holy Roman Emperor.

context_en: Approximately 66,000 people of Native American heritage live in Montana. A twelfth nation, the Little Shell Chippewa, a "landless" people headquartered in Great Falls, is recognized by the state of Montana, but not by the U.S. Government. The headquarters of the Blackfeet Nation are at the Browning Indian Reservation (1851) at the Browning Agency, the Crow Indian Reservation (1851) at the Crow Agency, the Northern Indian Reservation (1855) at Pablo, the Flathead Indian Reservation (1855) at Pend d'Oreille, northern Cheyenne at the Cheyenne Indian Reservation (1884), Fort at the Belknap Agency (1888), Fort Supreme at the Indian Reservation (1888), Poplar at the Fort Peck Indian Reservation (1888), and Chippewa Parbox Elder's Cree on the nearby Rocky Boy Indian Reservation (1916). About 63% of all Native people live off reservations, concentrated in large Montana cities with the largest concentration of urban Indians in Great Falls. The state also has a small Métis population, and 1990 census data indicated that people from 275 different tribes lived in Montana.

context_en: Political anthropology is concerned with the structure of political systems, viewed from the basis of the structure of society. While political anthropology developed as a discipline primarily concerned with politics in stateless societies, a new development began from the 1960s, and is still manifesting: anthropologists increasingly turn to "complex" social settings to study In which the presence of states, bureaucracies, and markets entered both ethnographic accounts and analyzes of local events. The turn towards complex societies meant that political issues were addressed at two main levels. At first, anthropologists continued to study political organization and political phenomena that lay outside the state-regulated sphere (in patron-client relationships or tribal political organization). Second, anthropologists gradually began to develop a disciplinary concern with states and their institutions (and with the relationship between formal and informal political institutions). An anthropology of the state developed, and today it is the most promising field. Geertz' comparative work on "Negara", the Balinese state, is an early, well-known example.
questions_en: Who did a comparative work on a Balinese state?

context_en: Despite their close genetic relationship and the ability to interbreed, there are several clinical characteristics to distinguish gray wolves from domestic dogs. Domesticated dogs are clearly distinguished from wolves by starch gel electrophoresis of red blood cell acid phosphatase. The tympanic bullae in gray wolves are large, convex, and almost spherical, while the bullae of dogs are small, compressed, and slightly ridged. Compared to wolves of similar size, dogs have 20% smaller skulls and 30% smaller brains.:35 Gray wolves also have proportionally larger teeth than dogs; The molars and molars of wolves are much less crowded and have more complex cusp patterns. Wolves do not have dewclaws on their back feet, unless mixed with dogs. Dogs lack a functioning pre-caudal gland, and enter estrus twice a year, unlike most gray wolves, which do so only once a year. Dogs require fewer calories to function than wolves. A dog's limp ears may be the result of atrophy of the jaw muscles. Domestic dogs have thicker skin than wolves, with some Inuit tribes favoring the former as clothing due to their greater resistance to wear and tear in harsh climates.
questions_en: Who usually has thicker skin, dogs or wolves?

context_en: Political economy in anthropology applies the principles and methods of historical materialism to the traditional concerns of anthropology, including but not limited to non-capitalist societies. Political economy introduced questions of history and colonialism to nonhistorical anthropological theories of social structure and culture. Three main areas of interest developed rapidly. The first of these areas belonged to "pre-capitalist" societies that were subject to evolutionary "tribal" stereotypes. Sahlin works on hunter-gatherers because the 'original affluent society' did much to perpetuate that image. The second area concerned the vast majority of the world's population at the time, farmers, many of whom were involved in the complex revolutionary wars in Vietnam. The third area was on colonialism, imperialism, and the creation of the capitalist world-system. More recently, these political economists have more directly addressed the issues of industrial (and post-industrial) capitalism around the world.
questions_en: What do farmers make up the vast majority of the world?

context_en: Since Whitehead's metaphysics described a universe in which all entities have experience, he needed a new way of describing perception that was not limited to living, self-aware beings. The word he coined was "prehension", which comes from the Latin prehensio, meaning "to seize." The word is meant to indicate a kind of perception that is conscious for people as well as electrons. Or may become unconscious. It is also clearly intended to reject Whitehead's theory of representational perception, in which the mind has only private thoughts about other entities. For Whitehead, the term "prehension" indicates that the perceiver actually incorporates aspects of the perceived thing into itself. These genes have been shown to impact the Catecholamine synthesis pathway, with most of the genes influencing the fight or flight response (i). selection for tameness), and emotional processing. context_en: All objects from everyday life that we can bump into, touch or squeeze are made of atoms. This atomic matter in turn interacts with subatomic particles – typically a nucleus of protons and neutrons, and a cloud of electrons. Generally, science considers these composite particulate matter because they have both rest mass and volume. In contrast, massive particles such as photons are not considered matter, because they have neither rest mass nor volume. However, all particles with rest mass have classical quantities, because fundamental particles such as quarks and leptons (sometimes equated with matter) are considered "point particles", with no effective size or volume. Nevertheless, quarks and leptons together form "normal matter", and their interactions contribute to the effective amount of the overall particles that make up normal matter.

context_en: Nanjing has a humid subtropical climate (Köppen Cfa) and is under the influence of the East Asian monsoon. The four seasons are distinct, with moist conditions seen throughout the year, a very hot and muggy summer, a cold, moist winter, and a fair length of fall in the middle, spring and autumn. Along with Chongqing and Wuhan, Nanjing is traditionally known as one of the "Three Fernancial Cities" along the Yangtze River (长江流域三大火炉) for its perennially high temperatures in summer. However, mid-June to late July is the plum blossom blooming season marked by Meiyu (the rainy season of East Asia; literally "plum rain"), during which the city experiences a period of light rain in the form of humidity. Typhoons are uncommon but possible in the late stages of summer and early part of autumn. The annual average temperature is about 15. 46 °C (59.8 °F), with a monthly 24-hour average temperature ranging from 2. 4 °C (36.3° F) in January to 27.8 °C (82.0° F) in July. Extremes since 1951 have occurred at -14. 0 °C (7 °F) to 40 on 6 January 1955. 7 °C (105 °F) on 22 August 1959. The average rainfall is 115 days a year, and the average annual rainfall is 1,062 millimeters (42 in). context_en: Antibiotics are tested for any negative effects on humans or other mammals before approval for clinical use, and are generally considered safe and most well tolerated. However, some antibiotics are associated with a range of adverse side effects. Side effects range from mild to very severe depending on the antibiotics used, the microbial organisms targeted, and the individual patient. Side effects may reflect the pharmacologic or toxicological properties of the antibiotic or include hypersensitivity reactions or anaphylaxis. The safety profile of new drugs is often not established even for those with a long history of use. Adverse effects range from fever and nausea to major allergic reactions, including photodermatitis and anaphylaxis. Common side effects include diarrhea, resulting from a disruption in the species composition of the intestinal flora, resulting, for example, in the overgrowth of pathogenic bacteria, such as Clostridium difficile. Antibiotics can also affect the vaginal flora, and may lead to overgrowth of yeast species of the genus Candida in the vulvo-vaginal area. Additional side effects may result from interactions with other drugs, such as increased risk of tendon damage from administration of a quinolone antibiotic with a systemic corticosteroid. Some scientists have speculated that indiscriminate use of antibiotics alters the host microbiota and is linked to chronic disease.
questions_en: What can happen when antibiotics are used with other medicines?

context_en: Chopin rarely performed publicly in Paris. In later years he usually gave a single annual concert at the Salle Polel, a venue that seated three hundred. He played more often in salons, but preferred to play in his Paris apartment for small groups of friends. The composer Arthur Hadley has observed that "as a pianist Chopin was unique in achieving a reputation of the highest order on the basis of a small number of public appearances—no more than thirty during his lifetime." The list of composers provides an indication of the richness of the artistic life of Paris during this period. Examples include a concert on 23 March 1833, in which Chopin, Liszt and Hiller performed a concerto (on piano) by J. Bach for three keyboards; and, on 3 March 1838, a concert in which Chopin, his student Adolphe Guttmann, Charles-Valentin Alkan, and Alkan's teacher Joseph Zimmermann conducted Alkan's concerto for eight hands in two movements from Beethoven's 7th Symphony. Arranged,. Chopin was also involved in the composition of Liszt's Hexameron; he wrote the sixth (and final) variation on Bellini's theme. Chopin's music soon found success with publishers, and in 1833 he contracted with Maurice Schlesinger, who published through his family connections not only in France, but also in Germany and England.

context_en: Despite their close genetic relationship and the ability to interbreed, there are several clinical characteristics to distinguish gray wolves from domestic dogs. Domesticated dogs are clearly distinguished from wolves by starch gel electrophoresis of red blood cell acid phosphatase. The tympanic bullae in gray wolves are large, convex, and almost spherical, while the bullae of dogs are small, compressed, and slightly ridged. Compared to wolves of similar size, dogs have 20% smaller skulls and 30% smaller brains.:35 Gray wolves also have proportionally larger teeth than dogs; The molars and molars of wolves are much less crowded and have more complex cusp patterns. Wolves do not have dewclaws on their back feet, unless mixed with dogs. Dogs lack a functioning pre-caudal gland, and enter estrus twice a year, unlike most gray wolves, which do so only once a year. Dogs require fewer calories to function than wolves. A dog's limp ears may be the result of atrophy of the jaw muscles. Domestic dogs have thicker skin than wolves, with some Inuit tribes favoring the former as clothing due to their greater resistance to wear and tear in harsh climates.

context_en: In the spring of 1834, Chopin attended the Lower Rhenish Music Festival at Aix-la-Chapelle with Hiller, and it was there that Chopin met Felix Mendelssohn. After the festival, the trio visited Düsseldorf, where Mendelssohn was appointed music director. He spent what Mendelssohn described as "a very agreeable day", playing and discussing music at his piano, and meeting Friedrich Wilhelm Schadow, director of the Academy of Art, and some of his distinguished pupils such as Low, Bendmann, Met Hildebrand and Sohn. In 1835 Chopin went to Carlsbad, where he spent time with his parents; the last time he would see them. On his way back to Paris, he met old friends from Warsaw, the Wodzińskis. He introduced his daughter Maria to Poland five years ago, when she was eleven. This meeting led him to stay for two weeks in Dresden, when he had previously intended to return to Paris via Leipzig. The composer's portrait of a sixteen-year-old girl, along with Delacroix's, are regarded as Chopin's best parallels. In October he finally reached Leipzig, where he met Schumann, Clara Wieck and Felix Mendelssohn, who performed for him his own oratorio St. Paul, and who considered him "an ideal musician". In July 1836 Chopin traveled with the Wodziński family to Marienbad and Dresden, and in September he proposed to Maria, whose mother Countess Wodzińska approved in principle. Chopin moved to Leipzig, where he presented Schumann with his G minor Ballade. At the end of 1836 he sent Maria an album in which her sister Ludwika had inscribed seven of his songs, and his 1835 Nocturne in C-sharp minor, Op. 27, no. The anodyne thank you he received from Maria proved to be the last letter he had.
questions_en: What was Friedrich Wilhelm Schadow's position?
answers_en: Director of the Academy of Art

context_en: Portugal has the most liberal laws regarding possession of illegal drugs in the Western world. In 2001, Portugal effectively decriminalized the possession of all drugs that are still illegal in other developed countries, including but not limited to cannabis, cocaine, heroin, and LSD. While possession is legal, trafficking and possession of more than "10 days' personal use" are still punishable by jail time and fines. People caught with small amounts of any drug are given the option to go to a rehabilitation facility, and can refuse treatment without consequences. Despite criticism from other European countries, which reported Portugal's drug consumption would increase significantly, overall drug use declined along with the number of cases of HIV infection, which had fallen 50 percent by 2009. Drug use also declined among 16- to 18-year-olds, although marijuana use rose slightly among that age group.

context_en: The ultimate real legacy of the Principia Mathematica is mixed. It is generally accepted that Kurt Gödel's incompleteness theorem of 1931 definitively demonstrated that for any set of axioms and inference rules proposed to unify mathematics, there must in fact be some truth of mathematics that can be determined. could not be deduced from them, and so the Principia Mathematica could never achieve its goal. However, Gödel could not have come to this conclusion without Whitehead and Russell's book. In this way, the legacy of the Principia Mathematica can be described as its key role in denying the possibility of achieving its own stated goals. But beyond this somewhat ironic legacy, the book popularized modern mathematical logic and drew important connections between logic, epistemology, and metaphysics.

context_en: On the other hand, the change through the Phanerozoic fits much better with hyperbolic models (widely used in population biology, demography and macrosociology, as well as fossil biodiversity) than with exponential and logistic models. The latter model implies that changes in diversity are guided by first order positive feedback (more ancestors, more descendants) and/or negative feedback resulting from resource limitation. The hyperbolic model implies a second-order positive feedback. The hyperbolic pattern of world population growth arises from a second-order positive feedback between population size and the rate of technological progress. The hyperbolic character of biodiversity growth can be equated to the feedback between diversity and community structure complexity. The similarity between biodiversity and human population curves probably comes from the fact that both are derived from the interference of hyperbolic trend with cyclical and stochastic dynamics.

context_en: Nanjing, for more than a thousand years one of the country's most important cities, is recognized as one of the four great ancient capitals of China, and was the world's largest city for hundreds of years, enjoying peace and prosperity. Nanjing served as the capital of Eastern Wu, one of the three major states in the Three Kingdoms period (211–280); Eastern Jin and each of the Southern dynasties (Liu Song, Southern Qi, Liang, and Chen), which ended in 317. -ruled southern China continuously from 589; the Southern Tang, one of the Ten Kingdoms (937–76); the Ming dynasty, for the first time, ruled all of China (1368–1421); and during the Chinese Civil War Republic of China before the flight to Taiwan (1927–37, 1945–49). It has served as the capital city of Jiangsu Province since the founding of China, and is still the nominal capital of the Republic of China housing many of its important heritage sites, including the Presidential Palace and the Sun Yat-sen Mausoleum. Nanjing is famous for human historical landscapes, mountains and waters such as Fujimiao, Ming Palace, Chatin Palace, porcelain tower, drum tower, stone city, city wall, Qianhui River, Xuanwu Lake and purple mountain. context_en: Antibiotics are tested for any negative effects on humans or other mammals before approval for clinical use, and are generally considered safe and most well tolerated. However, some antibiotics are associated with a range of adverse side effects. Side effects range from mild to very severe depending on the antibiotics used, the microbial organisms targeted, and the individual patient. Side effects may reflect the pharmacologic or toxicological properties of the antibiotic or include hypersensitivity reactions or anaphylaxis. The safety profile of new drugs is often not established even for those with a long history of use. Adverse effects range from fever and nausea to major allergic reactions, including photodermatitis and anaphylaxis. Common side effects include diarrhea, resulting from a disruption in the species composition of the intestinal flora, resulting, for example, in the overgrowth of pathogenic bacteria, such as Clostridium difficile. Antibiotics can also affect the vaginal flora, and may lead to overgrowth of yeast species of the genus Candida in the vulvo-vaginal area. Additional side effects may result from interactions with other drugs, such as increased risk of tendon damage from administration of a quinolone antibiotic with a systemic corticosteroid. Some scientists have speculated that indiscriminate use of antibiotics alters the host microbiota and is linked to chronic disease.
questions_en: What is an example of antibiotics that could have a possible side effect of tendon damage?
answers_en: a quinolone antibiotic with a systemic corticosteroid

context_en: Exposure to antibiotics early in life increases body mass in humans and mouse models. Early life is a critical period for the establishment of the intestinal microbiota and metabolic development. Mice exposed to the above antibiotic treatments (STAT) – either penicillin, vancomycin, penicillin and vancomycin, or chlortetracycline had altered composition of the gut microbiota as well as its metabolic capabilities. Additionally, research has shown that rats given low dose penicillin (1 μg/g body weight) around birth and throughout the lactation process had decreased body mass and fat mass, accelerated growth, and hepatic expression of genes involved in adipogenesis. Expression was increased in control rats. Furthermore, penicillin in combination with a high-fat diet rapidly increased insulin levels in rats. However, it is unclear whether antibiotics cause obesity in humans. Studies have found a correlation between early exposure to antibiotics (<6 months) and increased body mass (at 10 and 20 months). Another study found that the type of antibiotic exposure was also important, with those macrolides having the highest risk of overweight compared to penicillins and cephalosporins. Therefore, there is an association between antibiotic exposure in early life and obesity in humans, but whether there is a causal relationship is unclear. Although there is a correlation between antibiotic use in early life and obesity, the effect of antibiotics on obesity in humans must weigh against the beneficial effects of clinically indicated treatment with antibiotics in childhood.
questions_en: Do antibiotics increase the chance for humans to get fat?

context_en: Endemic species may be threatened with extinction through the process of genetic pollution, i. Uncontrolled hybridization, introgression and genetic quagmire. Genetic pollution leads to homogenization or replacement of the local genome resulting in numerical and/or fitness advantage of an introduced species. Hybridization and introgression are side effects of introduction and invasion. These events can be particularly harmful to rare species that come into contact with more abundant ones. Abundant species may be associated with rare species, depleting their gene pool. This problem is not always obvious from morphological (external appearance) observation. Some degree of gene flow is normal adaptation, and not all genes and genotype constellations may be conserved. However, hybridization, with or without introgression, nevertheless threatens the survival of rare species.

context_en: The successful outcome of antimicrobial therapy with antibacterial compounds depends on many factors. These include host defense mechanisms, site of infection, and the biochemical and pharmacodynamic properties of the antibacterial. These findings are based on laboratory studies, and have also been shown to eliminate bacterial infections in clinical settings. Since the activity of an antibacterial often depends on its concentration, in vitro characterization of antibacterial activity usually involves determining the minimum inhibitory concentration and the minimum bactericidal concentration of an antibacterial. To predict clinical outcome, the antimicrobial activity of an antibacterial is usually combined with its Pharmacokinetic profile, and several pharmacological parameters are used as markers of drug efficacy.

context_en: Reincarnation refers to a process whereby beings go through a succession of afterlife as one of several possible forms of life, each lasting from conception to death. According to Buddhism ultimately there is no such thing as a self independent from the rest of the universe. Buddhists also refer to themselves as believers of the Anatta doctrine—Nairetamyavadin or Anattvadin. context_en: Political economy in anthropology applies the principles and methods of historical materialism to the traditional concerns of anthropology, including but not limited to non-capitalist societies. Political economy introduced questions of history and colonialism to nonhistorical anthropological theories of social structure and culture. Three main areas of interest developed rapidly. The first of these areas belonged to "pre-capitalist" societies that were subject to evolutionary "tribal" stereotypes. Sahlin works on hunter-gatherers because the 'original affluent society' did much to perpetuate that image. The second area concerned the vast majority of the world's population at the time, farmers, many of whom were involved in the complex revolutionary wars in Vietnam. The third area was on colonialism, imperialism, and the creation of the capitalist world-system. More recently, these political economists have more directly addressed the issues of industrial (and post-industrial) capitalism around the world.

context_en: Intercrop crop diversity is, in part, responsible for offering diversity in what we eat. Interspecific diversity, the diversity of alleles within a single species, also affects what we like in our diet. If a crop fails in a monoculture, we rely on agricultural diversity to replant the land with something new. If a wheat crop is destroyed by an insect we can plant a hardier variety of wheat the next year, relying on the introgressed variety. We can produce wheat in that region and combine a different species altogether, relying on interspecific diversity. Even an agricultural society that grows primarily monocultures depends on biodiversity at some point.

context_en: Perhaps the single most influential device on the interpretation of these characters was the Teletype Model 33 ASR, which was a printing terminal with an available paper tape reader/punch option. Paper tape was a very popular medium for long-term program storage until the 1980s, being less expensive and in some ways less fragile than magnetic tape. Specifically, TeleType models had 33 machine assignment codes for 17 (control-q, dc 1, also known as xon), 19 (control-s, dc 3, also known as xoff), and 127 (delete. ) became the de facto standard. The Model 33 was also notable for carrying the description of Control-G (BEL, meaning alert operator) as the unit contained an actual bell which it described as BELL. Since the bug also showed a left arrow symbol for the O key (since ASCII-1963, which had this character instead of the underscore), a non-valued use of the code 15 (Control-O, Shift In) meant "Delete previous character". It was also adopted by many early timesharing systems but eventually became neglected.

context_en: Biodiversity, a contraction of "biological diversity", generally refers to the diversity and variability of life on Earth. One of the most widely used definitions defines it in terms of variability within species, between species, and between ecosystems. It is a measure of the diversity of organisms present in different ecosystems. It may refer to genetic variation, ecosystem variation, or species variation (number of species) within a region, biome, or planet. Terrestrial biodiversity tends to be greater near the equator, which appears to be a result of the warmer climate and higher primary productivity. Biodiversity is not distributed evenly on Earth. It is the richest in the tropics. Marine biodiversity is highest along the coasts in the western Pacific, where sea surface temperatures are highest and in mid-latitude bands of all oceans. There are latitudinal gradients in species diversity. Biodiversity is generally clustered in hotspots, and has been increasing through time, but will likely slow in the future.
questions_en: Where on Earth is biodiversity most abundant?
answers_en: It is the richest in the tropics

context_en: The ultimate real legacy of the Principia Mathematica is mixed. It is generally accepted that Kurt Gödel's incompleteness theorem of 1931 definitively demonstrated that for any set of axioms and inference rules proposed to unify mathematics, there must in fact be some truth of mathematics that can be determined. could not be deduced from them, and so the Principia Mathematica could never achieve its goal. However, Gödel could not have come to this conclusion without Whitehead and Russell's book. In this way, the legacy of the Principia Mathematica can be described as its key role in denying the possibility of achieving its own stated goals. But beyond this somewhat ironic legacy, the book popularized modern mathematical logic and drew important connections between logic, epistemology, and metaphysics.
questions_en: Despite its incompleteness, is the Principia now considered a valuable achievement of mathematics?
answers_en: The book popularized modern mathematical logic and drew important connections between logic, epistemology, and metaphysics.

context_en: From the beginning of the 16th century, both Western Armenia and Eastern Armenia fell under Iranian Persian rule. From the mid-16th century with the Peace of Amasya, and decisively from the first half of the 17th century with the Treaty of Zubab until the first half of the 19th century, Eastern Armenia was successively ruled by the Iranian Safavid, Affarid and Qajar empires. While Western Armenia remained under Ottoman rule. In the late 1820s, parts of historical Armenia under Iranian control centered on Iran and Lake Sevan (Eastern Armenia) were incorporated into the Russian Empire following Iran's forced ceding of power following its losses in the Russo-Persian War ( 1826--1828) and the subsequent Treaty of Turkmenchay. context_en: Political anthropology is concerned with the structure of political systems, viewed from the basis of the structure of society. While political anthropology developed as a discipline primarily concerned with politics in stateless societies, a new development began from the 1960s, and is still manifesting: anthropologists increasingly turn to "complex" social settings to study In which the presence of states, bureaucracies, and markets entered both ethnographic accounts and analyzes of local events. The turn towards complex societies meant that political issues were addressed at two main levels. At first, anthropologists continued to study political organization and political phenomena that lay outside the state-regulated sphere (in patron-client relationships or tribal political organization). Second, anthropologists gradually began to develop a disciplinary concern with states and their institutions (and with the relationship between formal and informal political institutions). An anthropology of the state developed, and today it is the most promising field. Geertz' comparative work on "Negara", the Balinese state, is an early, well-known example.

context_en: Genocide has become an official term in international relations. Genocide was not used before 1944. Earlier, in 1941, Winston Churchill described the mass murder of Russian prisoners of war and civilians as "a crime without a crime". That year, a Polish-Jewish lawyer named Raphael Lemkin described the policies of systematic murder instituted by the Nazis as genocide. The word genocide is a combination of the Greek prefix xeno- (meaning tribe or race) and cadre (the Latin word for killing). The term is defined as a specific set of violent crimes that are committed against a certain group with an attempt to remove the entire group from existence or destroy them.
questions_en: What is the etymology of the word "genocide"?

context_en: Antibiotics are tested for any negative effects on humans or other mammals before approval for clinical use, and are generally considered safe and most well tolerated. However, some antibiotics are associated with a range of adverse side effects. Side effects range from mild to very severe depending on the antibiotics used, the microbial organisms targeted, and the individual patient. Side effects may reflect the pharmacologic or toxicological properties of the antibiotic or include hypersensitivity reactions or anaphylaxis. The safety profile of new drugs is often not established even for those with a long history of use. Adverse effects range from fever and nausea to major allergic reactions, including photodermatitis and anaphylaxis. Common side effects include diarrhea, resulting from a disruption in the species composition of the intestinal flora, resulting, for example, in the overgrowth of pathogenic bacteria, such as Clostridium difficile. Antibiotics can also affect the vaginal flora, and may lead to overgrowth of yeast species of the genus Candida in the vulvo-vaginal area. Additional side effects may result from interactions with other drugs, such as increased risk of tendon damage from administration of a quinolone antibiotic with a systemic corticosteroid. Some scientists have speculated that indiscriminate use of antibiotics alters the host microbiota and is linked to chronic disease.
questions_en: Name some side effects?

context_en: All of Chopin's compositions involve piano. Most are for solo piano, although he also wrote two piano concertos, some chamber pieces, and some ballads for polish. His keyboard style is highly individual and often technically demanding; his own performances were noted for their perceptiveness and sensitivity. Chopin invented the concept of the instrumental ballad. His major piano works also include Mazurkas, Waltzes, Nocturnes, Polonaises, Études, Impromptus, Scherzos, Predudes and Sonatas, some published only after his death. Influences on his creative style include Polish folk music, the classical tradition of J. Bach, Mozart and Schubert, all of whose music he admired, as well as the Paris Salon where he was a frequent guest. Their innovations in style, musical form, and harmony, and their association with nationalism, were influential throughout and after the late Romantic period.

context_en: Several molecular mechanisms of antibacterial resistance exist. Intrinsic antibacterial resistance may be part of the genetic makeup of bacterial strains. For example, an antibiotic target may be absent from the bacterial genome. Acquired resistance results from a mutation in the bacterial chromosome or the acquisition of extra chromosomal DNA. Antibacterial-producing bacteria have evolved resistance mechanisms that have been shown to be similar, and have been transferred to antibacterial-resistant strains. The spread of antibacterial resistance often occurs through vertical transmission of mutations during evolution and by genetic recombination of DNA by horizontal genetic exchange. For example, antibacterial resistance genes can be exchanged through these resistance genes between different bacterial strains or species. Plasmids that carry several different resistance genes can confer multiple antibacterial resistance. Cross-resistance to multiple antibacterials can also occur when a resistance mechanism encoded by a single gene confers resistance to more than one antibacterial compound.
questions_en: What meets some resistance?

context_en: No-self (Pali: anatta; Sanskrit: anathaman) is the third mark of existence. The Nikayas are in Anatta not as a spiritual claim, but as an approach to attaining release from suffering. In fact, the Buddha rejected both the spiritual claims "I have a self" and "I have no self" as vegetative thoughts that tie one to suffering. context_en: The rise of bacterial resistance to antibiotics is a common phenomenon. The emergence of resistance often reflects evolutionary processes occurring during antibiotic therapy. Antibiotic treatment may select for bacterial strains with a physiologically or genetically increased ability to survive high doses of antibiotics. Under certain conditions, this may result in preferential growth of resistant bacteria, while the growth of sensitive bacteria is blocked by the drug. For example, antibacterial selection for strains containing antibacterial resistance genes was first demonstrated by the Luria–Delbruck experiment in 1943. Antibiotics such as penicillin and erythromycin, which used to have high efficacy against many bacterial species and strains, have become less effective, due to the increasing resistance of many bacterial strains.

context_en: Formal discipline is administered by the elders of the congregation. Destructive, a form of lashing, is the strongest form of discipline, with the offender being treated unpunished. Contact with disfellowshipped persons is limited to direct family members living in the same household, and with congregation elders who may invite disfellowshipped persons to apply for reinstatement; formal if contractually or financially obligated. Business dealings may continue. Witnesses are taught that avoiding social and spiritual interactions with disfellowshipped individuals keeps the congregation free from immoral influences and that "losing valuable fellowship with loved ones can help [the shunned individual] 'come to his senses' , 'See the seriousness of his wrongness, and take steps to return to Jehovah.' The practice of rocking may also serve to deter other members from disloyal behavior. Members who disassociate (formally resign) are described as wicked in Watch Tower Society literature and are even more appalled. Disfellowshipped persons may eventually be reinstated to the congregation if repentant by the elders in the congregation in which the disfellowshipment was made. Reparation is a shorter form of discipline formally given by a judicial committee to a baptized person who is considered to have repented of serious sin; the repentant person temporarily loses specific privileges of service, but has no access to social or spiritual fellowship. There is no restriction. Marking, social but not spiritual fellowship, is practiced if a baptized member commits serious, but not serious, sin in what is perceived as a violation of Biblical principles. [Note 4].

context_en: Before the beginning of the 20th century, treatments for infections were primarily based on medicinal folklore. Mixtures with antimicrobial properties that were used in the treatment of infections were described 2000 years ago. Many ancient cultures, including the ancient Egyptians and ancient Greeks, used specially selected molds and plant materials and extracted extracts to treat infections. More recent observations made in the laboratory of antibiosis among microorganisms initiated the discovery of natural antibacterials produced by microorganisms. Louis Pasteur observed, "If we could interfere with the rivalry observed between certain bacteria, it would perhaps offer the greatest hopes for therapeutics". The term 'antibiosis', meaning "against life", was introduced by the French bacteriologist Jean Paul Villemin as a descriptive name for the phenomenon exhibited by these early antibacterial drugs. Louis Pasteur and Robert Koch observed that antibiosis was first described in bacteria in 1877, when an airborne bacillus could inhibit the growth of Bacillus anthracis. These drugs were later named antibiotics by Selman Waksman, an American microbiologist in 1942. The science and development of antibacterials as synthetic antibiotic chemotherapy began in Germany with Paul Ehrlich in the late 1880s. Ehrlich noted that some dyes would color human, animal, or bacterial cells, while others did not. He then proposed the idea that it might be possible to create chemicals that would act as a selective drug that would bind and kill the bacteria without harming the human host. After screening hundreds of dyes against different organisms, in 1907, he discovered a medicinally useful drug, the synthetic antibacterial salvarsan now called arsphenamine.

context_en: Armenian literature dates back to 400 AD, when Mesop Mashtots invented the first Armenian alphabet. This period is often seen as the Golden Age of Armenian literature. Early Armenian literature was written by the "Father of Armenian History", Moses of Korin, who wrote a history of Armenia. The book covers the time-frame from the formation of the Armenian people to the fifth century AD. There is a great literary movement in the nineteenth century which was to give rise to modern Armenian literature. This period of time, during which Armenian culture flourished, is known as the Revival Period (Zartanki Sherchan). The revivalist writers of Constantinople and Tiflis, almost identical to the Romantics of Europe, were interested in encouraging Armenian nationalism. Most of them adopted newly created Eastern or Western forms of the Armenian language, depending on the target audience, and preferred them over Classical Armenian (Grabar). This period ended after the Hamidian Genocide, when the Armenians experienced turbulent times. As the 1920s and the Armenian history of the genocide became more openly discussed, writers such as Periyar Sevak, Gevork Emin, Silva Kaputikyan and Hovhannes Shiraz began a new era of literature.

context_en: A dense wave of smoke began to spread over central and eastern parts of China on 2 December 2013, covering a distance of about 1,200 kilometers (750 mi), including Tianjin, Hebei, Shandong, Jiangsu, Anhui, Shanghai and Zhejiang. The lack of cold airflow, combined with slow-moving air masses carrying industrial emissions, caused airborne pollutants to accumulate to form a thick layer of smog over the area. Heavy smoke heavily polluted central and southern Jiangsu province, especially in and around Nanjing, for five straight days with "severely polluted" and "heavily polluted" for nine. On December 3, 2013, PM2 levels. The mean average concentration averaged over 943 micrograms per cubic metre, falling to 338 micrograms per cubic meter on 4 December 2013. Between 3:00 a.m., December 3, and 2:00 a.m., December 4 local time, several expressways from Nanjing to other Jiangsu cities were closed, grounding dozens of passenger buses at the Zhongyangmen bus station. From December 5 to 6, Nanjing issued a red alert for air pollution and closed all kindergarten through middle schools. Children's hospital outpatient services increased by 33 percent; common incidences of bronchitis, pneumonia, upper respiratory tract infections increased significantly. The smog ended on 12 December. Officials blamed the dense pollution on lack of air, automobile exhaust emissions under low air pressure, and the lack of coal-powered district heating systems in the northern China region. The prevailing winds blew low-hanging air masses of factory emissions (mostly SO2) toward the east coast of China.

By about 1900, Russell had organized thousands of part- and full-time colporteurs, and was appointing foreign missionaries and establishing branch offices. By the 1910s, Russell's organization maintained about a hundred "pilgrims" or traveling preachers. context_en: To put it another way, a thing or person is often seen as having a "defined essence" or "core identity" that is immutable, and describes what the thing or person really is. In this way of thinking, things and people are seen as fundamentally identical over time, with any changes being qualitative and secondary to their core identity (e. "Mark's hair has turned gray because he He's grown older, but he's still the same person"). But in Whitehead's cosmology, the only fundamentally existing things are separate "occasions of experience" that overlap each other in time and space, and jointly make up an enduring person or thing. On the other hand, common thinking often treats "the essence of something" or "a person's identity/core" as the most important or salient characteristics of that person or thing at a given time. One of its essence is generalization. Identities don't define people, people define identities. Everything changes from moment to moment, and to think of anything as having a "permanent essence" misses the fact that "all things flow", although this is often a useful way of speaking.

context_en: Burnside rules, similar to those of American football, were consolidated by Orfe in 1903, in an attempt to distinguish it from a more rugby-oriented game. The Burnside rules were reduced to 12 men per side, introduced the snap-back system, required the offensive team to gain 10 yards on three downs, allowed throws from the sideline, allowed only six men on the line. , said all goals kicked were worth two points and the opposition was within 10 yards of the defender on all kicks. The rules were an attempt to standardize rules across the country. SARFU, QRFU and CRU at first refused to adopt the new rules. Forward passes were not allowed in the Canadian game until 1929, and touchdowns, which were worth five points, were increased to six points in 1956, in both cases several decades after the Americans made the same change. The primary differences between the Canadian and American games stem from rule changes that the American side of the border adopted but not the Canadian side (originally, both sides had three downs, goal posts at the goal lines and unlimited forward speed, but the American side adopted Did not modify these rules and Canadians). Canadian field width was a rule that was not based on American rules, as Canadian games were played on wider fields and in stadiums that were not as narrow as American stadiums.

context_en: Approximately 66,000 people of Native American heritage live in Montana. A twelfth nation, the Little Shell Chippewa, a "landless" people headquartered in Great Falls, is recognized by the state of Montana, but not by the U.S. Government. The headquarters of the Blackfeet Nation are at the Browning Indian Reservation (1851) at the Browning Agency, the Crow Indian Reservation (1851) at the Crow Agency, the Northern Indian Reservation (1855) at Pablo, the Flathead Indian Reservation (1855) at Pend d'Oreille, northern Cheyenne at the Cheyenne Indian Reservation (1884), Fort at the Belknap Agency (1888), Fort Supreme at the Indian Reservation (1888), Poplar at the Fort Peck Indian Reservation (1888), and Chippewa Parbox Elder's Cree on the nearby Rocky Boy Indian Reservation (1916). About 63% of all Native people live off reservations, concentrated in large Montana cities with the largest concentration of urban Indians in Great Falls. The state also has a small Métis population, and 1990 census data indicated that people from 275 different tribes lived in Montana.

context_en: According to R. Rummel, genocide has 3 different meanings. The general meaning is the killing by the government of people because of their national, ethnic, racial, or religious group membership. The legal meaning of genocide refers to the international treaty, the Convention on the Prevention and Punishment of the Crime of Genocide. It also includes non-killings that ultimately destroy the group, such as preventing births or forcibly transferring children from one group to another. A generalized meaning of genocide is similar to the ordinary meaning, but also includes government killings or otherwise deliberate killing of political opponents. To avoid confusion about what this means, Rummel created the term democide for the third meaning.

The headquarters of the Blackfeet Nation are at the Browning Indian Reservation (1851) at the Browning Agency, the Crow Indian Reservation (1851) at the Crow Agency, the Northern Indian Reservation (1855) at Pablo, the Flathead Indian Reservation (1855) at Pend d'Oreille, northern Cheyenne at the Cheyenne Indian Reservation (1884), Fort at the Belknap Agency (1888), Fort Supreme at the Indian Reservation (1888), Poplar at the Fort Peck Indian Reservation (1888), and Chippewa Parbox Elder's Cree on the nearby Rocky Boy Indian Reservation (1916). About 63% of all Native people live off reservations, concentrated in large Montana cities with the largest concentration of urban Indians in Great Falls. The state also has a small Métis population, and 1990 census data indicated that people from 275 different tribes lived in Montana.

context_en: From his diagrams of a small number of particles interacting in spacetime, Feynman could model all of physics in terms of the extent of the coupling of those particles' spins and fundamental forces. Feynman attempted to explain the strong interactions governing nuclei called the partner model. The Parton model emerged as a complement to the quark model developed by his Caltech colleague Murray Gell-Mann. The relationship between the two models was unclear; Gell-Mann presented Feynman's parton as a "put-on". In the mid-1960s, physicists believed that quarks were just a bookkeeping device for symmetry numbers, not real particles, as in the figure of the omega-minus particle, if it was interpreted as three identical strange quarks. , so it seemed impossible if quarks were real. Stanford linear accelerator deep inelastic scattering experiments in the late 1960s showed, similarly to the 1911 experiment on scattering alpha particles on gold nuclei, that nucleons (protons and neutrons) scattered electrons as point-like particles. implied. It was natural to identify these with quarks, but Feynman's parton model attempted to explain the experimental data in a way that did not introduce additional hypotheses. For example, the data showed that some 45% of the energy motion was carried by electrically-neutral particles in the nucleus. These electrically-neutral particles are now seen to be gluons that carry the forces between quarks and also carry the three-valued color quantum number that solves the omega-minus problem. Feynman did not dispute the quark model; for example, when the fifth quark was discovered in 1977, Feynman immediately told his students that the discovery implied the existence of a sixth quark, discovered in the decade after his death. I went.
questions_en: Which model was developed by Murray Gell-Mann?

context_en: In physics, Whitehead's ideas have had some influence. He expressed a view that might perhaps be considered a form of Einstein's general relativity, see Whitehead's theory of gravitation. This has been seriously criticized. Yutaka Tanaka, who suggests that the gravitational constant disagrees with experimental findings, proposes that Einstein's work does not actually refute Whitehead's formulation. Whitehead's view has now been rendered obsolete with the discovery of gravitational waves. Those phenomena have been observed locally that violate the local flatness of large-scale space that Whitehead assumes. As a result, Whitehead's universe should be treated as a local conjecture, and his notion of a similar spatio-temporal geometry, the Minkoloskian, should often be treated as a locally-sufficient conjecture. An accurate replacement of Whitehead's cosmology would require accepting Riemannian geometry. Furthermore, although Whitehead himself gave only secondary consideration to quantum theory, the metaphysics of processes has proven attractive to some physicists in that field. Henry Stapp and David Boehm are among those whose work has been influenced by Whitehead.

context_en: In late 1831, Chopin received his first major endorsement from an outstanding contemporary when Robert Schumann, reviewing Op. 2 Variations in the Allgemeine Musikalische Zeitung (his first published article on music), declared: "Salute, gentlemen! Taking no models, he has found, if not a complete renewal of piano music, an abundance of original ideas of a kind not found anywhere else. "After this concert, Chopin realized that his essentially intimate keyboard technique was not optimal for larger concert spaces. Later that year she was introduced to the wealthy Rothschild banking family, whose patronage also opened the doors for her to other private salons (aristocracy and social gatherings of the artistic and literary elite). By the end of 1832 Chopin had established himself among the musical elite of Paris, and had earned the respect of his peers such as Hill, Liszt, and Berlioz. context_en: From September 1823 to 1826 Chopin attended the Warsaw Lyceum, where he received organ lessons from the Czech composer Wilhelm Wurfel during his first year. In the autumn of 1826 he began a three-year course under the Silesian composer Józef Elsner at the Warsaw Conservatory, studying music theory, bass and composition. [n3] During this period he continued to write and to give recitals in concerts and salons in Warsaw. He was engaged by the inventors of a mechanical organ, the "Eolomelodikon", and in May 1825 on this instrument he performed his own improvisations and part of a concerto by Moscheles. The success of this concert led to an invitation from Tsar Alexander I, who was visiting Warsaw, to perform a similar citation on the first instrument; the tsar presented him with a diamond ring. At the subsequent Éolomelodikon concert on 10 June 1825, Chopin performed his Rondo Op. It was the first of his works to be published commercially and earned him his first mention in the foreign press, when the Leipzig Allgemeine Musikalische Zeitung praised its "wealth of musical ideas".

context_en: In Whitehead's view, then, concepts such as "quality", "matter", and "form" are problematic. These fail to adequately account for change in "classical" concepts, and ignore the active and experiential nature of the world's most basic elements. They are useful abstractions, but not the basic building blocks of the world. What a person is usually conceived of, for example, is philosophically described as a continuum of overlapping events. After all, people change all the time, if only because they are older than the second and have had some more experiences. These occasions of experience are logically distinct, but progressively linked in what Whitehead calls a "society" of events. By assuming that enduring objects are the most real and fundamental things in the universe, materialists mistake the abstract for the concrete (what Whitehead calls the "fallacy of misplaced objects").

context_en: On the other hand, the change through the Phanerozoic fits much better with hyperbolic models (widely used in population biology, demography and macrosociology, as well as fossil biodiversity) than with exponential and logistic models. The latter model implies that changes in diversity are guided by first order positive feedback (more ancestors, more descendants) and/or negative feedback resulting from resource limitation. The hyperbolic model implies a second-order positive feedback. The hyperbolic pattern of world population growth arises from a second-order positive feedback between population size and the rate of technological progress. The hyperbolic character of biodiversity growth can be equated to the feedback between diversity and community structure complexity. The similarity between biodiversity and human population curves probably comes from the fact that both are derived from the interference of hyperbolic trend with cyclical and stochastic dynamics.

context_en: Matter typically exists in four states (or phases): solid, liquid and gas, and plasma. For most of the history of the natural sciences people have pondered the precise nature of matter. context_en: Nanjing has a humid subtropical climate (Köppen Cfa) and is under the influence of the East Asian monsoon. The four seasons are distinct, with moist conditions seen throughout the year, a very hot and muggy summer, a cold, moist winter, and a fair length of fall in the middle, spring and autumn. Along with Chongqing and Wuhan, Nanjing is traditionally known as one of the "Three Fernancial Cities" along the Yangtze River (长江流域三大火炉) for its perennially high temperatures in summer. However, mid-June to late July is the plum blossom blooming season marked by Meiyu (the rainy season of East Asia; literally "plum rain"), during which the city experiences a period of light rain in the form of humidity. Typhoons are uncommon but possible in the late stages of summer and early part of autumn. The annual average temperature is about 15. 46 °C (59.8 °F), with a monthly 24-hour average temperature ranging from 2. 4 °C (36.3° F) in January to 27.8 °C (82.0° F) in July. Extremes since 1951 have occurred at -14. 0 °C (7 °F) to 40 on 6 January 1955. 7 °C (105 °F) on 22 August 1959. The average rainfall is 115 days a year, and the average annual rainfall is 1,062 millimeters (42 in). With monthly percent possible sunshine ranging from 37 percent in March to 52 percent in August, the city receives 1,983 hours of bright sunshine annually.
questions_en: Does monsoon affect Nanjing?

context_en: Matter typically exists in four states (or phases): solid, liquid and gas, and plasma. A focus on the elementary-particle view of matter also leads to new phases of matter, such as quark–gluon plasma. For most of the history of the natural sciences people have pondered the precise nature of matter. The idea that matter was composed of discrete building blocks, the so-called particle theory, was first put forward by the Greek philosophers Leucippus (~490 BC) and Democritus (~470–380 BC).

context_en: Originally based on the English alphabet, ASCII encodes 128 specified characters into seven-bit integers as shown by the ASCII chart at right. For example, lowercase J would become binary 1101010 and decimal 106. ASCII contains definitions for 128 characters: 33 non-printing control characters (many now obsolete) that affect how text and spaces are processed and 95 printable characters, including spaces (which are Considered an invisible graphic: 223).

context_en: In 1976, Walter Fiers at Ghent University (Belgium) was the first to establish the complete nucleotide sequence of a viral RNA-genome (bacteriophage MS2). The following year, Fred Sanger completed the first DNA-genome sequence: phage-X174, of 5386 base pairs. The first complete genome sequences between all three domains of life were released within a short period during the mid-1990s: the first bacterial genome to be sequenced was that of Haemophilus influenzae, which was obtained in a 1995 study at The Institute for Genomic Research. Was completed by the team. A few months later, the first eukaryotic genome was completed, with the sequence of 16 chromosomes of the budding yeast Saccharomyces cerevisiae published, the result of a European-led effort that began in the mid-1980s. The first genome sequence for an archaeon, Methanococcus jannaschii, was completed in 1996, again by The Institute for Genomic Research.

context_en: Brazil's Atlantic Forest is considered one such hotspot, containing approximately 20,000 plant species, 1,350 vertebrates, and millions of insects, about half of which occur nowhere else. [citation needed] Madagascar and the island of India are also particularly noteworthy. Colombia is characterized by high biodiversity, with the highest rate of species diversity by area unit worldwide and the largest number of species (species that do not occur naturally anywhere else) of any country. About 10% of the Earth's species can be found in Colombia, with over 1,900 species of birds, more than Europe and North America combined, Colombia has 10% of the world's mammalian species, 14% of the amphibian species, and 18% of the world's bird species. Madagascar's dry deciduous forests and lowland rainforest have a high proportion of endemism. [citation needed] Since the island separated from mainland Africa 66 million years ago, many species and ecosystems have evolved independently. [citation needed] Indonesia's 17,000 islands cover 735,355 square miles (1,904,560 km2) and contain 10% of the world's flowering plants, 12% of the mammals, and 17% of the reptiles, amphibians, and birds, with approximately 240 million individuals. Are included. Many areas of high biodiversity and/or endemism arise from specialized habitats that require unusual adaptations, for example, alpine environments in high mountains, or northern European peat bogs. [citation needed].
questions_en: How many plant species are there in Brazil's Atlantic Forest?

context_en: Most early home computer systems developed their own 8-bit character sets containing line-drawing and game glyphs, and often some or all of the control characters filled in with more than 0-31 graphics. Kaypro CP/M computers used the "upper" 128 characters for the Greek alphabet. The IBM PC defined code 437, which replaced control-characters with graphic symbols such as smiley faces, and mapped additional graphic characters to the upper 128 positions. Operating systems such as DOS supported these code pages, and manufacturers of the IBM PC supported them in the hardware. Digital Equipment Corporation developed the Multinational Character Set (DEC-MCS) for use in the popular VT220 terminal as one of the first extensions designed more for international languages ​​than block graphics. context_en: Nanjing has a humid subtropical climate (Köppen Cfa) and is under the influence of the East Asian monsoon. The four seasons are distinct, with moist conditions seen throughout the year, a very hot and muggy summer, a cold, moist winter, and a fair length of fall in the middle, spring and autumn. Along with Chongqing and Wuhan, Nanjing is traditionally known as one of the "Three Fernancial Cities" along the Yangtze River (长江流域三大火炉) for its perennially high temperatures in summer. However, mid-June to late July is the plum blossom blooming season marked by Meiyu (the rainy season of East Asia; literally "plum rain"), during which the city experiences a period of light rain in the form of humidity. Typhoons are uncommon but possible in the late stages of summer and early part of autumn. The annual average temperature is about 15. 46 °C (59.8 °F), with a monthly 24-hour average temperature ranging from 2. 4 °C (36.3° F) in January to 27.8 °C (82.0° F) in July. Extremes since 1951 have occurred at -14. 0 °C (7 °F) to 40 on 6 January 1955. 7 °C (105 °F) on 22 August 1959. The average rainfall is 115 days a year, and the average annual rainfall is 1,062 millimeters (42 in). With monthly percent possible sunshine ranging from 37 percent in March to 52 percent in August, the city receives 1,983 hours of bright sunshine annually.

context_en: Hydrogen production technologies became an important area of ​​solar chemical research from the 1970s. In addition to electrolysis driven by photovoltaic or photochemical cells, several thermochemical processes have also been explored. One such route uses concentrators to split water into oxygen and hydrogen at high temperatures (2,300–2,600 °C or 4,200–4,700 °F). Another approach uses heat from solar concentrates to drive steam reforming of natural gas thereby increasing the overall hydrogen yield compared to conventional reforming methods. Thermochemical cycles characterized by decomposition and regeneration of recombination present another avenue for hydrogen production. The SolZinc process under development at the Weizmann Institute uses a 1 MW solar furnace to decompose zinc oxide (ZnO) at temperatures above 1,200 °C (2,200 °F). This initial reaction produces pure zinc, which can then be reacted with water to produce hydrogen.

context_en: When people say that the genome of a sexually reproducing species has been "sequenced", usually they are referring to the determination of the sequences of a set of autosomes and one of each type of sex chromosome, which together potentially represent the sexes. Colloquially, the phrase "genetic makeup" is sometimes used to denote the genome of a particular individual or organism. context_en: Despite their close genetic relationship and the ability to interbreed, there are several clinical characteristics to distinguish gray wolves from domestic dogs. Domesticated dogs are clearly distinguished from wolves by starch gel electrophoresis of red blood cell acid phosphatase. The tympanic bullae in gray wolves are large, convex, and almost spherical, while the bullae of dogs are small, compressed, and slightly ridged. Compared to wolves of similar size, dogs have 20% smaller skulls and 30% smaller brains.:35 Gray wolves also have proportionally larger teeth than dogs; The molars and molars of wolves are much less crowded and have more complex cusp patterns. Wolves do not have dewclaws on their back feet, unless mixed with dogs. Dogs lack a functioning pre-caudal gland, and enter estrus twice a year, unlike most gray wolves, which do so only once a year. Dogs require fewer calories to function than wolves. A dog's limp ears may be the result of atrophy of the jaw muscles. Domestic dogs have thicker skin than wolves, with some Inuit tribes favoring the former as clothing due to their greater resistance to wear and tear in harsh climates.

context_en: Mahayana Buddhism received important theoretical grounding from Nagarjuna (probably c. 150–250 CE), arguably the most influential scholar within the Mahayana tradition. Nāgārjuna's primary contribution to Buddhist philosophy was the systematic exposition of the concept of śśnyatā, or "emptiness", which was widely attested in the Prajñapāmita sutras that emerged in his era. The concept of emptiness brings together a rejection of other major Buddhist doctrines, particularly anatta and dependent origination, the metaphysics of Sarvottvāda and Sautrantika (extinct non-Mahayana school). For Nāgārjuna, it is not only sentient beings that are empty of āman; all phenomena (dharma) are without any sentient (literally "self-nature" or "self-nature"), and thus without any inherent of essence; they are "empty" of independent being; thus the heterodox doctrines of the self circulating in time were rejected based on the principles of early Buddhism. Nagarjuna's school of thought is known as Dadhamaka. Some writings attributed to Nāgārjuna made explicit references to Mahayana texts, but argued his philosophy within the parameters set by the Agamas. He may have arrived at his positions from a desire to achieve a consistent exegesis of the Buddha's doctrine as recorded in the canon. In Nagarjuna's view the Buddha was not merely a precursor but the founder of the Madhyayaka system.
questions_en: What is the meaning of religions?

context_en: To put it another way, a thing or person is often seen as having a "defined essence" or "core identity" that is immutable, and describes what the thing or person really is. "Mark's hair has turned gray because he He's grown older, but he's still the same person"). On the other hand, common thinking often treats "the essence of something" or "a person's identity/core" as the most important or salient characteristics of that person or thing at a given time. context_en: The different stages of digestion include: cephalic phase, gastric phase, and intestinal phase. The cephalic phase occurs at the sight, thought, and smell of food, which stimulates the cerebral cortex. Taste and smell stimuli are sent to the hypothalamus and medulla oblongata. It is then routed through the vagus nerve and release of acetylcholine occurs. In this phase gastric secretion increases to 40% of the maximum rate. Acidity in the stomach is not buffered by food at this point and thus acts to inhibit parietal (secreted acid) and G cell (secreted gastrin) activity through D cell secretion of somatostatin. The gastric phase takes 3 to 4 hours. It is stimulated by gastric distention, presence of food in the stomach, and decreased pH. Distension activates the long and myenteric reflexes. This activates the release of acetylcholine, which stimulates the release of more gastric juices. As the protein enters the stomach, it binds with hydrogen ions, which increases the pH of the stomach. Inhibition of gastrin and gastric acid secretion is raised. This triggers the G cells to release gastrin, which in turn stimulates the parietal cells to secrete gastric acid. Gastric acid is approximately 0. 5% hydrochloric acid (HCl), which lowers the pH to the desired pH of 1-3. Acid release is also triggered by acetylcholine and histamine. The intestinal phase consists of two parts, stimulatory and inhibitory. Partially digested food fills the duodenum. This triggers the intestines to release gastrin. The enterogastric reflex inhibits the vagus nucleus, activates sympathetic fibers thereby forcing the pyloric sphincter to prevent more food from entering, and inhibits local reflexes.
questions_en: How is the gastric phase stimulated to begin?
answers_en: Stomach distension, presence of food in the stomach and decrease in pH

context_en: Montana Territory was created on April 26, 1864, when U. Organic Act passed. Schools began to be officially constructed in the area as families began to settle in the area. The first schools were subscription schools usually held in the teacher's home. The first formal school on record was at Fort Owen in the Bitterroot Valley in 1862. The students were Indian children and children of Fort Owen employees. The first school term started in early winter and lasted only until 28 February. Classes were taught by Shri. Robinson. Another early subscription school was started by Thomas Dimsdale in Virginia City in 1863. Students at this school were charged $1. 75 per week. The Montana Territorial Legislative Assembly had its inaugural meeting in 1864. The first legislature authorized counties to levy taxes for schools, which set the foundation for public schooling. Madison County was the first to take advantage of the newly authorized taxes and in 1886 the FHE First Public School was formed in Virginia City. The first school year was scheduled to begin in January 1866, but severe weather postponed its opening until March. The first school year ran through the summer and did not end until August 17. One of the first teachers at the school was Sarah Raymond. She was a 25-year-old woman who traveled to Virginia City via wagon train in 1865. To become a certified teacher, Raymond took a test in his home and paid a $6 fee in gold dust to receive a teaching certificate. With the help of an assistant teacher, Smt. Farley was responsible for teaching 50 to 60 students each day out of the 81 students enrolled at the Raymond School. Sarah Raymond was paid at the rate of $125 per month, and Mrs. Foley was paid $75 per month. There were no textbooks in the school. In their place was an assortment of books brought by various immigrants. Sarah dropped out the following year, but would later become Madison County Superintendent.

context_en: Antibiotics are tested for any negative effects on humans or other mammals before approval for clinical use, and are generally considered safe and most well tolerated. However, some antibiotics are associated with a range of adverse side effects. Side effects range from mild to very severe depending on the antibiotics used, the microbial organisms targeted, and the individual patient. Side effects may reflect the pharmacologic or toxicological properties of the antibiotic or include hypersensitivity reactions or anaphylaxis. The safety profile of new drugs is often not established even for those with a long history of use. Adverse effects range from fever and nausea to major allergic reactions, including photodermatitis and anaphylaxis. Common side effects include diarrhea, resulting from a disruption in the species composition of the intestinal flora, resulting, for example, in the overgrowth of pathogenic bacteria, such as Clostridium difficile. Antibiotics can also affect the vaginal flora, and may lead to overgrowth of yeast species of the genus Candida in the vulvo-vaginal area. Additional side effects may result from interactions with other drugs, such as increased risk of tendon damage from administration of a quinolone antibiotic with a systemic corticosteroid. Some scientists have speculated that indiscriminate use of antibiotics alters the host microbiota and is linked to chronic disease.
