context_en: Antibiotics are tested for any negative effects on humans or other mammals before approval for clinical use, and are generally considered safe and most well tolerated. However, some antibiotics are associated with a range of adverse side effects. Side effects range from mild to very severe depending on the antibiotics used, the microbial organisms targeted, and the individual patient. Side effects may reflect the pharmacologic or toxicological properties of the antibiotic or include hypersensitivity reactions or anaphylaxis. The safety profile of new drugs is often not established even for those with a long history of use. Adverse effects range from fever and nausea to major allergic reactions, including photodermatitis and anaphylaxis. Common side effects include diarrhea, resulting from a disruption in the species composition of the intestinal flora, resulting, for example, in the overgrowth of pathogenic bacteria, such as Clostridium difficile. Antibiotics can also affect the vaginal flora, and may lead to overgrowth of yeast species of the genus Candida in the vulvo-vaginal area. Additional side effects may result from interactions with other drugs, such as increased risk of tendon damage from administration of a quinolone antibiotic with a systemic corticosteroid. Some scientists have speculated that indiscriminate use of antibiotics alters the host microbiota and is linked to chronic disease.
questions_en: Photodermatitis, nausea, allergic reactions, and anaphylaxis are all types of what?

Some evidence suggests that invasive species are competitive in their new habitats because they are subject to less pathogen disturbance. Others report evidence that sometimes suggests that species-rich communities harbor many native and exotic species while some say that diverse ecosystems are more resilient and resist invasive plants and animals. Overall gamma diversity may be reduced as species become extinct for other reasons, but even some of the most inevitable invaders (E. : Dutch elm disease, emerald ash borer, chestnut blight in North America) have not caused extinction of their host species. Extinction, population decline, and homogenization of regional biodiversity are very common. context_en: Montana has a large Native American population both numerically and percentage-wise. States. context_en: A dense wave of smoke began to spread over central and eastern parts of China on 2 December 2013, covering a distance of about 1,200 kilometers (750 mi), including Tianjin, Hebei, Shandong, Jiangsu, Anhui, Shanghai and Zhejiang. The lack of cold airflow, combined with slow-moving air masses carrying industrial emissions, caused airborne pollutants to accumulate to form a thick layer of smog over the area. Heavy smoke heavily polluted central and southern Jiangsu province, especially in and around Nanjing, for five straight days with "severely polluted" and "heavily polluted" for nine. On December 3, 2013, PM2 levels. The mean average concentration averaged over 943 micrograms per cubic metre, falling to 338 micrograms per cubic meter on 4 December 2013. Between 3:00 a.m., December 3, and 2:00 a.m., December 4 local time, several expressways from Nanjing to other Jiangsu cities were closed, grounding dozens of passenger buses at the Zhongyangmen bus station. From December 5 to 6, Nanjing issued a red alert for air pollution and closed all kindergarten through middle schools. Children's hospital outpatient services increased by 33 percent; common incidences of bronchitis, pneumonia, upper respiratory tract infections increased significantly. The smog ended on 12 December. Officials blamed the dense pollution on lack of air, automobile exhaust emissions under low air pressure, and the lack of coal-powered district heating systems in the northern China region. The prevailing winds blew low-hanging air masses of factory emissions (mostly SO2) toward the east coast of China.

context_en: Since life began on Earth, five major mass extinctions and several minor events have led to large and sudden drops in biodiversity. The Phanerozoic Eon (the last 540 million years) saw a rapid increase in biodiversity through the Cambrian explosion – a period during which the majority of paleontology first appeared. Repeated over the next 400 million years, massive biodiversity losses classified as mass extinction events occurred. In Carbonfarmer, rainforest collapse caused a major loss of plant and animal life. The worst was the Permian–Triassic extinction event 251 million years ago; vertebrate recovery took 30 million years. The most recent, the Cretaceous–Paleogene extinction event, occurred 65 million years ago and often receives more attention than others because it resulted in the extinction of the dinosaurs.
questions_en: What happened in the Carboniferous?
answers_en: Rainforest collapse caused a huge loss of plant and animal life

context_en: In 1939, coinciding with the beginning of World War II, René Dubos reported the discovery of the first naturally derived antibiotic, tyrothricin, a compound of 20% gramicicin and 80% tyrosidine, from B. brevis. context_en: Phage therapy is another option being looked at to treat resistant strains of bacteria. The way researchers are doing this is by infecting pathogenic bacteria with their own viruses, more specifically, bacteriophages. Bacteriophages, also known simply as phages, are virulent bacterial viruses that infect bacteria by disrupting pathogenic bacterial lytic cycles. By disrupting the lytic cycles of bacteria, phages destroy their metabolism, which ultimately results in cell death. The phages will insert their DNA into the bacteria, allowing their DNA to be transcribed. Once their DNA has been transferred the cell will proceed to form new phages and as they are ready to be released, the cell will lyse. One of the concerns with using phages to fight pathogens is that the phages will infect "good" bacteria, or bacteria that are important in humans' everyday function. However, studies have proven that the phages are very specific when they target bacteria, which leads researchers to believe that sterile therapy is the surest path to defeat antibiotic-resistant bacteria.
questions_en: What has been talked about to treat resistant bacteria?

context_en: However, it should be stressed that for Whitehead God is not tied to religion. Whitehead said that these ordered capacities exist in what he called God's primitive nature. However, Whitehead was also interested in religious experience. context_en: Exposure to antibiotics early in life increases body mass in humans and mouse models. Early life is a critical period for the establishment of the intestinal microbiota and metabolic development. Mice exposed to the above antibiotic treatments (STAT) – either penicillin, vancomycin, penicillin and vancomycin, or chlortetracycline had altered composition of the gut microbiota as well as its metabolic capabilities. Additionally, research has shown that rats given low dose penicillin (1 μg/g body weight) around birth and throughout the lactation process had decreased body mass and fat mass, accelerated growth, and hepatic expression of genes involved in adipogenesis. Expression was increased in control rats. Furthermore, penicillin in combination with a high-fat diet rapidly increased insulin levels in rats. However, it is unclear whether antibiotics cause obesity in humans. Studies have found a correlation between early exposure to antibiotics (<6 months) and increased body mass (at 10 and 20 months). Another study found that the type of antibiotic exposure was also important, with those macrolides having the highest risk of overweight compared to penicillins and cephalosporins. Therefore, there is an association between antibiotic exposure in early life and obesity in humans, but whether there is a causal relationship is unclear. Although there is a correlation between antibiotic use in early life and obesity, the effect of antibiotics on obesity in humans must weigh against the beneficial effects of clinically indicated treatment with antibiotics in childhood.

According to Buddhism ultimately there is no such thing as a self independent from the rest of the universe. Buddhists also refer to themselves as believers of the Anatta doctrine—Nairetamyavadin or Anattvadin. Reincarnation in subsequent existences should be understood as a continuation of the dynamic, ever-changing process of pratityasamutpada ("dependent arising") determined by one existence (karma) rather than as a function of rebirth from one existence to the next.

context_en: Nanjing (listen; Chinese: 南京, "Southern Capital") is a city located in the heartland of the lower Yangtze River region in China, which has long been a major center of culture, education, research, politics, economy, transportation networks, and tourism. . It is the largest city in Jiangsu province of the People's Republic of China and the second largest city in East China, with a total population of 8,216,100, and is de jure the capital of the Republic of China, having lost the mainland during the civil war. The city that bears its name, the "Southern Capital", has a prominent place in Chinese history and culture, having served as the capitals of various Chinese dynasties, empires, and republican governments from the 3rd century AD to 1949. Before the advent of pinyin romanization, the city name of Nanjing was written as Nanking or Nanqin. Nanjing has several other names, and some historical names are now used as the names of districts of the city, and among them is the name Jiangning (江寧), the former character of which is part of Jiang (江, river), the former name Jiangsu and The latter character Ning (寧, simplified form 宁, peace) is a diminutive of Nanjing. When the state capital is, for example, the ROC, Jing (京) is adopted as the abbreviation for Nanjing. Although a city located in the southern part of China became the Chinese national capital as early as the Jin Dynasty, the name Nanjing was changed to designate the city a thousand years later in the Ming Dynasty. Nanjing is typically known as Jinling (金陵, literally meaning Gold Mountain) and the older name is used after the Warring States period in the Zhou dynasty.

context_en: As at most other universities, Notre Dame students run several news media outlets. The nine student-run outlets include three newspapers, a radio and television station, and several magazines and journals. Begun as a one-page journal in September 1876, the educational journal is issued twice monthly and claims to be the oldest continuing collegiate publication in the United States. The other magazine, Juglar, is released twice a year and focuses on student literature and artwork. The Dome is published annually. The newspapers have rival publishing interests, with the Observer published daily and primarily reporting university and other news, and staffed by students from both Notre Dame and Saint Mary's Colleges. Unlike Scholarly and The Dome, the Observer is an independent publication and has no faculty advisors or any editorial oversight from the university. In 1987, when some students believed that the Observer began to show a conservative bias, a liberal newspaper, Common Sense, was published. Similarly, in 2003, when other students believed the paper showed a liberal bias, the conservative paper Irish Rover went into production. Neither paper is published as frequently as the Observer; however, all three are distributed to all students. Finally, in spring 2008 Beyond Politics, a graduate journal for political science research, made its debut.

context_en: From his diagrams of a small number of particles interacting in spacetime, Feynman could model all of physics in terms of the extent of the coupling of those particles' spins and fundamental forces. Feynman attempted to explain the strong interactions governing nuclei called the partner model. The Parton model emerged as a complement to the quark model developed by his Caltech colleague Murray Gell-Mann. The relationship between the two models was unclear; Gell-Mann presented Feynman's parton as a "put-on". In the mid-1960s, physicists believed that quarks were just a bookkeeping device for symmetry numbers, not real particles, as in the figure of the omega-minus particle, if it was interpreted as three identical strange quarks. , so it seemed impossible if quarks were real. Stanford linear accelerator deep inelastic scattering experiments in the late 1960s showed, similarly to the 1911 experiment on scattering alpha particles on gold nuclei, that nucleons (protons and neutrons) scattered electrons as point-like particles. implied. It was natural to identify these with quarks, but Feynman's parton model attempted to explain the experimental data in a way that did not introduce additional hypotheses. For example, the data showed that some 45% of the energy motion was carried by electrically-neutral particles in the nucleus. These electrically-neutral particles are now seen to be gluons that carry the forces between quarks and also carry the three-valued color quantum number that solves the omega-minus problem. Feynman did not dispute the quark model; for example, when the fifth quark was discovered in 1977, Feynman immediately told his students that the discovery implied the existence of a sixth quark, discovered in the decade after his death. I went.
questions_en: What model did Feynman use to complement the quark model?

context_en: However, based on Mahayana, Tibeto-Mongolian Buddhism is one of the schools that practice Vajrayana or "Diamond Vehicle" (also called Mantrayana, Nerva, Tantricism, or esoteric Buddhism). On 11 August, three weeks after completing his studies at the Warsaw Conservatory, he made his debut in Vienna. He gave two piano concerts and received many favorable reviews – apart from some commenting (in Chopin's own words) that he was "too delicate for those accustomed to the piano-bashing of local artists". At one of these concerts, he premiered his Variations on El Ci Darm La Mano, Op. 2 (Variations on an Aria from Mozart's opera Don Giovanni) for piano and orchestra. context_en: Nanjing, for more than a thousand years one of the country's most important cities, is recognized as one of the four great ancient capitals of China, and was the world's largest city for hundreds of years, enjoying peace and prosperity. Took and enjoyed wars and disasters. Nanjing served as the capital of Eastern Wu, one of the three major states in the Three Kingdoms period (211–280); Eastern Jin and each of the Southern dynasties (Liu Song, Southern Qi, Liang, and Chen), which ended in 317. -ruled southern China continuously from 589; the Southern Tang, one of the Ten Kingdoms (937–76); the Ming dynasty, for the first time, ruled all of China (1368–1421); and during the Chinese Civil War Republic of China before the flight to Taiwan (1927–37, 1945–49). The city also served as the seat of the rebellious Taiping Heavenly Kingdom (1851–64) and the Japanese puppet regime of Wang Jingwei (1940–45) during the Second Sino-Japanese War, and endured atrocities in both conflicts, including the Nanjing Massacre. It has served as the capital city of Jiangsu Province since the founding of China, and is still the nominal capital of the Republic of China housing many of its important heritage sites, including the Presidential Palace and the Sun Yat-sen Mausoleum. Nanjing is famous for human historical landscapes, mountains and waters such as Fujimiao, Ming Palace, Chatin Palace, porcelain tower, drum tower, stone city, city wall, Qianhui River, Xuanwu Lake and purple mountain. context_en: Matter should not be confused with mass, as the two are not quite the same in modern physics. For example, mass is a conserved quantity, meaning that its value is invariant through time within a closed system. However, no matter is conserved in such systems, although this is not obvious under normal circumstances on Earth, where matter is nearly conserved. Nevertheless, special relativity shows that matter can disappear by conversion into energy, even inside closed systems, and it can also be created from energy within such systems. However, because mass (like energy) can be neither created nor destroyed, the amount of mass and the amount of energy remain the same during the transformation of a substance (which represents a fixed amount of energy). Does) Non-material (i). , non-matter) energy. This is true even in the reverse change of energy.

context_en: In China, a call to boycott the French hypermart Carrefour from May 1 began spreading via mobile text messaging from April 1 and online chat rooms on weekends from April 2, according to the company's major shareholder, LVMH Group. context_en: All of Chopin's compositions involve piano. Most are for solo piano, although he also wrote two piano concertos, some chamber pieces, and some ballads for polish. His keyboard style is highly individual and often technically demanding; his own performances were noted for their perceptiveness and sensitivity. Chopin invented the concept of the instrumental ballad. His major piano works also include Mazurkas, Waltzes, Nocturnes, Polonaises, Études, Impromptus, Scherzos, Predudes and Sonatas, some published only after his death. Influences on his creative style include Polish folk music, the classical tradition of J. Bach, Mozart and Schubert, all of whose music he admired, as well as the Paris Salon where he was a frequent guest. Their innovations in style, musical form, and harmony, and their association with nationalism, were influential throughout and after the late Romantic period.

context_en: Biodiversity provides important support for drug discovery and availability of medicinal resources. A significant proportion of drugs are derived directly or indirectly from biological sources: at least 50% of pharmaceutical compounds on the US market are derived from plants, animals, and micro-organisms, while approximately 80% of the world's population depends on primary health care. For medicines from nature (used in modern or traditional medical practice). Only a small fraction of wild species have been investigated for medical potential. Biodiversity has been important to advances in the entire field of bionics. Evidence from market analysis and biodiversity science suggests that the decline in production from the pharmaceutical sector since the mid-1980s can be attributed to the move away from natural product exploration ("bioprospecting") in favor of genomics and synthetic chemistry. , in fact claims about the value of undiscovered pharmaceuticals may not provide sufficient incentives for companies in free markets due to the high cost of developing them; meanwhile, natural products have a potential to support important economic and health innovation. Has a long history. Marine ecosystems are particularly important, although inappropriate bioprospecting can exacerbate biodiversity loss, as well as violate the regulations of the communities and states from which resources are taken.

context_en: During the century of internecine struggle for dominance between the northern Christian kingdoms, the County of Portugal formed the southern part of the Kingdom of Galicia. Sometimes the Kingdom of Galicia existed independently for short periods, but usually formed an important part of the Kingdom of León. During this period, the people of the counties of Portugal styled themselves as Galicians, struggling to maintain the autonomy of Galicia with its distinct language and culture (Galician-Portuguese) from the Lyonnais culture, even when the Kingdom of Galicia was divided. The situation changed in relation to the Kingdom of Lyon. As a result of political division, Gallican-Portuguese lost its unity when the Counties of Portugal separated from the Kingdom of Galicia (a dependent Kingdom of León) to establish the Kingdom of Portugal. The Galician and Portuguese versions of the language then diverged over time as they followed independent evolutionary paths. This happened when the Kingdom of León and the United Kingdom of Castile and the Castilian language (known as Spanish) slowly began to influence the Galician language over the centuries and then tried to replace it. The same thing happened with the Astral-Leonese language to the point where it was little or completely replaced by Castilian (the Spanish language).

context_en: Digestion of some fats may begin in the mouth where lingual lipase breaks down some short chain lipids into diglycerides. However, fat is primarily digested in the small intestine. The presence of fat in the small intestine produces hormones that stimulate the release of pancreatic lipase from the pancreas and bile from the liver that helps in the emulsification of fat for the absorption of fatty acids. Complete digestion of a molecule of fat (a triglyceride) results in a mixture of fatty acids, mono- and di-glycerides, as well as some undigested triglycerides, but no free glycerol molecules.
questions_en: What does bile from the liver help with?

context_en: However, it should be stressed that for Whitehead God is not tied to religion. Rather than springing primarily from religious faith, Whitehead saw God as essential to his spiritual system. His system required that there exist an order among the possibilities, an order that permitted novelty in the world and provided a purpose to all entities. Whitehead said that these ordered capacities exist in what he called God's primitive nature. However, Whitehead was also interested in religious experience. This led him to reflect more intensely on what he saw as God's second nature, the consequential nature. Whitehead's concept of God as a "dipolar" entity has called for fresh theological thinking.

context_en: Perhaps the single most influential device on the interpretation of these characters was the Teletype Model 33 ASR, which was a printing terminal with an available paper tape reader/punch option. Specifically, TeleType models had 33 machine assignment codes for 17 (control-q, dc 1, also known as xon), 19 (control-s, dc 3, also known as xoff), and 127 (delete. ) became the de facto standard. The Model 33 was also notable for carrying the description of Control-G (BEL, meaning alert operator) as the unit contained an actual bell which it described as BELL. Since the bug also showed a left arrow symbol for the O key (since ASCII-1963, which had this character instead of the underscore), a non-valued use of the code 15 (Control-O, Shift In) meant "Delete previous character". context_en: The different stages of digestion include: cephalic phase, gastric phase, and intestinal phase. The cephalic phase occurs at the sight, thought, and smell of food, which stimulates the cerebral cortex. Taste and smell stimuli are sent to the hypothalamus and medulla oblongata. It is then routed through the vagus nerve and release of acetylcholine occurs. In this phase gastric secretion increases to 40% of the maximum rate. Acidity in the stomach is not buffered by food at this point and thus acts to inhibit parietal (secreted acid) and G cell (secreted gastrin) activity through D cell secretion of somatostatin. The gastric phase takes 3 to 4 hours. It is stimulated by gastric distention, presence of food in the stomach, and decreased pH. Distension activates the long and myenteric reflexes. This activates the release of acetylcholine, which stimulates the release of more gastric juices. As the protein enters the stomach, it binds with hydrogen ions, which increases the pH of the stomach. Inhibition of gastrin and gastric acid secretion is raised. This triggers the G cells to release gastrin, which in turn stimulates the parietal cells to secrete gastric acid. Gastric acid is approximately 0. 5% hydrochloric acid (HCl), which lowers the pH to the desired pH of 1-3. Acid release is also triggered by acetylcholine and histamine. The intestinal phase consists of two parts, stimulatory and inhibitory. Partially digested food fills the duodenum. This triggers the intestines to release gastrin. The enterogastric reflex inhibits the vagus nucleus, activates sympathetic fibers thereby forcing the pyloric sphincter to prevent more food from entering, and inhibits local reflexes.
questions_en: How long does the gastric phase take?

context_en: In Whitehead's view, then, concepts such as "quality", "matter", and "form" are problematic. These fail to adequately account for change in "classical" concepts, and ignore the active and experiential nature of the world's most basic elements. They are useful abstractions, but not the basic building blocks of the world. What a person is usually conceived of, for example, is philosophically described as a continuum of overlapping events. After all, people change all the time, if only because they are older than the second and have had some more experiences. These occasions of experience are logically distinct, but progressively linked in what Whitehead calls a "society" of events. By assuming that enduring objects are the most real and fundamental things in the universe, materialists mistake the abstract for the concrete (what Whitehead calls the "fallacy of misplaced objects").
questions_en: Why did he believe that those concepts were wrong?
answers_en: These fail to adequately account for change in "classical" concepts, and ignore the active and experiential nature of the world's most basic elements.

context_en: In the spring of 1834, Chopin attended the Lower Rhenish Music Festival at Aix-la-Chapelle with Hiller, and it was there that Chopin met Felix Mendelssohn. After the festival, the trio visited Düsseldorf, where Mendelssohn was appointed music director. He spent what Mendelssohn described as "a very agreeable day", playing and discussing music at his piano, and meeting Friedrich Wilhelm Schadow, director of the Academy of Art, and some of his distinguished pupils such as Low, Bendmann, Met Hildebrand and Sohn. In 1835 Chopin went to Carlsbad, where he spent time with his parents; the last time he would see them. On his way back to Paris, he met old friends from Warsaw, the Wodzińskis. He introduced his daughter Maria to Poland five years ago, when she was eleven. This meeting led him to stay for two weeks in Dresden, when he had previously intended to return to Paris via Leipzig. The composer's portrait of a sixteen-year-old girl, along with Delacroix's, are regarded as Chopin's best parallels. In October he finally reached Leipzig, where he met Schumann, Clara Wieck and Felix Mendelssohn, who performed for him his own oratorio St. Paul, and who considered him "an ideal musician". In July 1836 Chopin traveled with the Wodziński family to Marienbad and Dresden, and in September he proposed to Maria, whose mother Countess Wodzińska approved in principle. Chopin moved to Leipzig, where he presented Schumann with his G minor Ballade. At the end of 1836 he sent Maria an album in which her sister Ludwika had inscribed seven of his songs, and his 1835 Nocturne in C-sharp minor, Op. 27, no. The anodyne thank you he received from Maria proved to be the last letter he had.

context_en: Montana Territory was created on April 26, 1864, when U. Organic Act passed. Schools began to be officially constructed in the area as families began to settle in the area. The first schools were subscription schools usually held in the teacher's home. The first formal school on record was at Fort Owen in the Bitterroot Valley in 1862. The students were Indian children and children of Fort Owen employees. The first school term started in early winter and lasted only until 28 February. Classes were taught by Shri. Robinson. Another early subscription school was started by Thomas Dimsdale in Virginia City in 1863. Students at this school were charged $1. 75 per week. The Montana Territorial Legislative Assembly had its inaugural meeting in 1864. The first legislature authorized counties to levy taxes for schools, which set the foundation for public schooling. Madison County was the first to take advantage of the newly authorized taxes and in 1886 the FHE First Public School was formed in Virginia City. The first school year was scheduled to begin in January 1866, but severe weather postponed its opening until March. The first school year ran through the summer and did not end until August 17. One of the first teachers at the school was Sarah Raymond. She was a 25-year-old woman who traveled to Virginia City via wagon train in 1865. To become a certified teacher, Raymond took a test in his home and paid a $6 fee in gold dust to receive a teaching certificate. With the help of an assistant teacher, Smt. Farley was responsible for teaching 50 to 60 students each day out of the 81 students enrolled at the Raymond School. Sarah Raymond was paid at the rate of $125 per month, and Mrs. Foley was paid $75 per month. There were no textbooks in the school. In their place was an assortment of books brought by various immigrants. Sarah dropped out the following year, but would later become Madison County Superintendent.
questions_en: When was the first public school built in Virginia City?

context_en: European regulators introduced Basel III rules for banks. It increased capital ratios, limits on leverage, narrow definition of capital (to exclude subordinate debt), limit counter-party risk, and new liquidity requirements. Critics argue that Basel III does not address the problem of faulty risk-weighting. Major banks suffered losses from AAA-ratings created by financial engineering (which creates apparently risk-free assets from high-risk collateral) which requires less capital as per Basel II. Lending to AA rated sovereigns has a risk-weight of zero, thus leading to lending to governments and the next crisis. Johan Norberg argues that the regulations (Basel III among others) have actually led to excessive lending to risky governments (see European sovereign-debt crisis) and that the ECB is lending even more as a solution.

context_en: The origin of the domestic dog (Canis lupus familiaris or Canis familiaris) is unclear. Whole genome sequencing indicates that the dog, the gray wolf, and the extinct Taymir wolf diverged at the same time, 27,000–40,000 years ago. These dates mean that the earliest dogs arose during the time of human hunters and not agriculturalists. Modern dogs are more closely related to ancient wolf fossils that have been found in Europe than to modern gray wolves. The genetic closeness of almost all dog breeds to the gray wolf is due to admixture, except for many Arctic dog breeds which are close to the Taimyr wolf of North Asia.

context_en: Muammar Gaddafi was born in a tent near Qasr Abu Hadi, a rural area outside the city of Sirte in the western Libyan desert. His family came from a small, relatively non-influential tribal group called the Kaddhapha, who were Berber by heritage. His father Mohammed Abdul Salam bin Hamed bin Mohammed was known as Abu Menyar (died 1985), and his mother was named Aisha (died 1978); Abu Menyar was a goat and camel herder. Earned a meager subsistence as. Nomadic Bedouins, they were illiterate and kept no birth records. context_en: In June 1837 Chopin visited London incognito in the company of the piano maker Camille Pleyel where he played at a musical soiree at the home of the English piano maker James Broadwood. Upon his return to Paris, his collaboration with Sands began in earnest, and by the end of June 1838 they had become lovers. Sands, who was six years older than the composer, and who had a series of lovers, wrote at this time: "I must say I was confused and amazed at the influence of this little creature. I still remember my astonishment. "The two spent an unhappy winter in Majorca (from 8 November 1838 to 13 February 1839), where, with the two children of Sands, , he had traveled in the hope of improving the health of Chopin and Sand's 15-year-old son Maurice, and also to escape threats from Sand's former lover Félicien Mallefil after discovering that the couple was not married. Majorca's deeply traditional Catholic population became obsolete, making accommodation difficult to find, forcing the group to live in a former Carthusian monastery in Valldemossa, which offered little shelter from the cold winter weather.

context_en: The different stages of digestion include: cephalic phase, gastric phase, and intestinal phase. The cephalic phase occurs at the sight, thought, and smell of food, which stimulates the cerebral cortex. Taste and smell stimuli are sent to the hypothalamus and medulla oblongata. It is then routed through the vagus nerve and release of acetylcholine occurs. In this phase gastric secretion increases to 40% of the maximum rate. Acidity in the stomach is not buffered by food at this point and thus acts to inhibit parietal (secreted acid) and G cell (secreted gastrin) activity through D cell secretion of somatostatin. The gastric phase takes 3 to 4 hours. It is stimulated by gastric distention, presence of food in the stomach, and decreased pH. Distension activates the long and myenteric reflexes. This activates the release of acetylcholine, which stimulates the release of more gastric juices. As the protein enters the stomach, it binds with hydrogen ions, which increases the pH of the stomach. Inhibition of gastrin and gastric acid secretion is raised. This triggers the G cells to release gastrin, which in turn stimulates the parietal cells to secrete gastric acid. Gastric acid is approximately 0. 5% hydrochloric acid (HCl), which lowers the pH to the desired pH of 1-3. Acid release is also triggered by acetylcholine and histamine. The intestinal phase consists of two parts, stimulatory and inhibitory. Partially digested food fills the duodenum. This triggers the intestines to release gastrin. The enterogastric reflex inhibits the vagus nucleus, activates sympathetic fibers thereby forcing the pyloric sphincter to prevent more food from entering, and inhibits local reflexes.
questions_en: What are the three digestive stages?
answers_en: Cephalic stage, gastric stage, and intestinal stage

context_en: Tracks of the Northern Pacific Railroad (NPR) reached Montana from the west in 1881 and from the east in 1882. These conflicts, in part, contributed to the Panic of 1873 which delayed the construction of railroads in Montana. Surveys in 1874, 1875, and 1876 helped spark the Great Sioux War of 1876. The transcontinental NPR was completed at Gold Creek on September 8, 1883.

context_en: Congo's democratic progress was derailed in 1997 when Lissouba and Sassou began fighting for power in a civil war. On 5 June, forces of President Lissoba's government surrounded Sassou's compound in Brazzaville and Sassou ordered members of his personal militia (known as "Cobras") to resist. Thus began a four-month conflict that destroyed or damaged Brazzaville and led to the deaths of thousands of civilians. context_en: The city of Nanjing was raised after the Sui dynasty took it over. It changed its name to Shenzhou (昇州) in the Tang dynasty and revived during the late Tang. It was chosen as the capital and called Jinling (金陵) during the Southern Tang (937–976), a state that succeeded the Wu state. It changed its name to Jiangning (江寧) in the Northern Song dynasty and to Jiankang in the Southern Song dynasty. Jiankang's textile industry flourished and expanded during the Song dynasty despite the constant threat of foreign invasions from the north from the Jurchen-led Jin dynasty. The court of Da Chu, a short-lived puppet state established by the Chechens, and the court of Song were once in the city. The city was eventually abolished by the Mongol Empire under the Yuan dynasty, further consolidating the city's status as a center of the textile industry.
questions_en: Who defeated the court of song?

context_en: France: The torch relay leg in Paris, held on 7 April, started on the first level of the Eiffel Tower and finished at the Stade Charliet. The relay was initially scheduled to cover 28 km, but this was shortened at the demand of Chinese authorities after widespread protests by pro-Tibet and human rights activists, who repeatedly attempted to disrupt, obstruct or stop the procession. did. A scheduled ceremony at the town hall was cancelled, and at the request of Chinese officials, the torch ended the relay by bus rather than being carried by the athletes. Paris city officials had announced plans to greet the Olympic flame with a peaceful protest when the torch was to reach the French capital. The city government attached a banner reading "Paris defends human rights" to the city hall, in an effort to promote the values ​​of all humanity and human rights." Members of Journalists Without Borders joined the mass protest. Came out for. An estimated 3,000 French police guarded the Olympic torch relay as it passed the Eiffel Tower and criss-crossed Paris amid the threat of protesters. Widespread pro-Tibet protests, including an attempt by more than one protestor to extinguish the flame with water or fire extinguishers, relay officers throwing the flame five times (according to police officials in Paris) and one on a bus. The torch was induced to be loaded, at the demand of the Chinese authorities. This was rejected by the Chinese Ministry of Foreign Affairs, despite video footage broadcast by the French television network France 2, which showed Chinese flame attendants extinguishing the torch. Backup flames accompany the relay at all times to relieve the torch. French judoka and torchbearer David Doyle expressed his bewilderment at the Chinese flame attendants who extinguished the torch, which he was about to hand over to Teddy Riner: "I understand that they are afraid of everything, but this is just annoying. They Extinguished the flame despite the fact that there was no risk, and they could see it and I don't know why they did it.

context_en: When people say that the genome of a sexually reproducing species has been "sequenced", usually they are referring to the determination of the sequences of a set of autosomes and one of each type of sex chromosome, which together potentially represent the sexes. Colloquially, the phrase "genetic makeup" is sometimes used to denote the genome of a particular individual or organism. Canis familiaris is used for domestic dogs. Although taxonomically it should probably be synonymous with Canis lupus." In 1982, the first edition of Mammal Species of the World listed Canis familiaris under Canis lupus with the comment: "Probably ancestral to the domestic dog. , Canis familiaris has priority over Canis lupus, but both were published together in Linnaeus (1758), and Canis lupus has been used universally for this species", which refers to the wolf as a member of the family. context_en: Biodiversity, a contraction of "biological diversity", generally refers to the diversity and variability of life on Earth. One of the most widely used definitions defines it in terms of variability within species, between species, and between ecosystems. It is a measure of the diversity of organisms present in different ecosystems. It may refer to genetic variation, ecosystem variation, or species variation (number of species) within a region, biome, or planet. Terrestrial biodiversity tends to be greater near the equator, which appears to be a result of the warmer climate and higher primary productivity. Biodiversity is not distributed evenly on Earth. It is the richest in the tropics. Marine biodiversity is highest along the coasts in the western Pacific, where sea surface temperatures are highest and in mid-latitude bands of all oceans. There are latitudinal gradients in species diversity. Biodiversity is generally clustered in hotspots, and has been increasing through time, but will likely slow in the future.

context_en: By 1763, the war in Central Europe was essentially a stalemate. Frederick kept Silesia and much of Saxony, but not the latter's capital, Dresden. His financial situation was not dire, but his kingdom was devastated and his army seriously weakened. His manpower had decreased dramatically, and he had lost so many effective officers and generals that a new offensive was probably impossible. British subsidies were stopped by the new Prime Minister Lord Beauty, and the Russian Emperor was overthrown by his wife Catherine, who ended Russia's alliance with Prussia and withdrew from the war. Austria, however, like most participants, was facing a severe financial crisis and had to reduce the size of its army, which greatly affected its offensive power. Indeed, after effectively maintaining a long war, its administration was in disarray. By that time, it still held Dresden, southeastern parts of Saxony, the County of Glatz, and southern Silesia, but the chances of victory were dim without Russian support. In 1763 a peace agreement was reached at the Treaty of Hubertusburg, ending the war in Central Europe.
questions_en: What was the result of the weakness of both Prussia and Austria?
answers_en: A peace agreement was reached at the Treaty of Hubertusburg in 1763, ending the war in Central Europe.

context_en: In Whitehead's view, then, concepts such as "quality", "matter", and "form" are problematic. These fail to adequately account for change in "classical" concepts, and ignore the active and experiential nature of the world's most basic elements. They are useful abstractions, but not the basic building blocks of the world. What a person is usually conceived of, for example, is philosophically described as a continuum of overlapping events. After all, people change all the time, if only because they are older than the second and have had some more experiences. These occasions of experience are logically distinct, but progressively linked in what Whitehead calls a "society" of events. By assuming that enduring objects are the most real and fundamental things in the universe, materialists mistake the abstract for the concrete (what Whitehead calls the "fallacy of misplaced objects").
questions_en: What basic concepts did Whitehead believe were questionable?

context_en: Although the two displayed great respect and admiration for each other, their friendship was uneasy and had some of the qualities of a love-hate relationship. Harold C. Schoenberg believes that Chopin displayed "jealousy and chauvinistic inclinations" toward Liszt's virtuosity at the piano, and others have also argued that he was charmed with Liszt's theatricality, exploits, and success. Liszt was the dedicatee of Chopin's Op. 10 études, and their performance prompted the composer to write to Hiller, "I should like to be robbed of the manner of my studies." However, Chopin expressed troubles in 1843 when Liszt wrote in one of his essays performed with the addition of several complex decorations, to which Chopin remarked that he should not have written the music or played it without apologizing. Most of Chopin's biographers state that the two had little to do with each other thereafter, although in his letters, dated as late as 1848, he still referred to her as "my friend Liszt". Some commentators point to events in the romantic lives of the two men as causing a rift between them; there are claims that Liszt displayed jealousy of his mistress Marie d'Agoult's obsession with Chopin, while others believe That Chopin had become concerned about Liszt's growing relationship with George Sand.

context_en: Violations of the rules are punished with a penalty, usually a loss of 5, 10 or 15 yards of yardage against the penalized team. Depending on the penalty, penalty yards may be assessed from the original line of scrimmage, from where the violation occurred (for example, for a pass interference violation), or from where the ball ended up after the play. A penalty on offense may, or may not, result in a loss; a penalty on defense may result in an offense already awarded automatically. For particularly serious conduct, the game official(s) may eject the players (ejected players may be replaced), or in exceptional cases, declare the game over and award a victory to one side or the other. The penalty does not affect the yard line over which the offense must reach to get a first down (unless a first down could be scored as a result of a penalty); if a penalty against the defense is being gained in first down yards , then the offense is awarded first down.

context_en: The torch was lit in a park at AT&T Park at approximately 1:17 p.m. PDT (20:17 UTC), briefly held aloft by American and Chinese Olympic officials. At approximately 2 p.m. PDT (21:00 UTC), the torch was resurfaced approximately 3 km (1 in) away. 9 miles) away from the stadium along Van Ness Avenue, a heavily trafficked thoroughfare that was not on the official route plans. Television reports showed Flamm being trailed by motorcycles and uniformed police officers. Two torchbearers carried the flame slowly behind a truck and surrounded by Olympic security guards. During the torch relay, the two torchbearers, Andrew Michael, who uses a wheelchair and is the vice president for sustainable development for the Bay Area Council and director of partnerships for change, and Marez Carter, an environmental lawyer, displayed Tibetan flags in protest. managed to do so, resulting in his withdrawal from the relay. The closing ceremony at Justin Herman Plaza was canceled due to the presence of a large number of protesters at the site. The torch run ended with a final stretch through San Francisco's Marina District and it was transferred to a bus to San Francisco International Airport for a temporary closing ceremony in the terminal, which excluded free media. context_en: Each play constitutes a down. The offense must advance the ball at least ten yards toward the opponents' goal line within three downs or forfeit the ball to their opponents. Once the offense has gained ten yards a new set of three downs (rather than the four downs given in American football). Does not accumulate at the bottom. If the offensive team gains 10 yards on their first play, they lose the other two downs and are given another set of threes. If a team fails to gain ten yards on two downs they usually punt the ball on third down or attempt to kick a field goal (see below) depending on their position on the field. . The team, however, can use its third down to advance the ball and gain a cumulative 10 yards.

context_en: Applied anthropology refers to the application of the method and theory of anthropology to the analysis and solution of practical problems. It is a, "complex of related, research-based, instrumental methods that produce change or stability in specific cultural systems through the provision of data, initiation of direct action, and/or formulation of policy". More simply, applied anthropology is the practical side of anthropological research; it involves researcher participation and activism within the participating community. It is closely related to evolutionary anthropology (distinct from the more important anthropology of evolution).

context_en: The move was motivated by an inclination by the British – as well as for practical reasons – to avoid large-scale commitments of troops on the continent. In the Seven Years' War, the English chose as their principal partner the greatest of the day, Frederick the Great of Prussia, then a rising power in Central Europe, and paid Frederick substantial subsidies for his campaigns. :106 This was accomplished in the Diplomatic Revolution of 1756, in which Britain ended its long-term alliance with Austria in favor of Prussia, leaving Austria with France. In marked contrast to France, Britain actively prosecuted the war in the colonies, taking full advantage of its naval power. :64–66 The British pursued a dual strategy – naval blockade and bombardment of enemy ports, and rapid movement of troops by sea. context_en: In 1977, Gaddafi dissolved the republic and created a new socialist state, the Jamahiriya ("people's state"). A particularly hostile relationship developed with the United States and the United Kingdom, resulting in the 1986 U.N. The bombing of Libya and UN-imposed economic sanctions. Rejecting his previous ideological commitments, from 1999 onwards Gaddafi encouraged economic privatization and sought rapprochement with Western countries, while also embracing Pan-Africanism and helping to establish the African Union. Amid the Arab Spring, an anti-Gadda rebellion led by the National Transitional Council (NTC) broke out in 2011, resulting in the Libyan Civil War. context_en: European regulators introduced Basel III rules for banks. Critics argue that Basel III does not address the problem of faulty risk-weighting. Major banks suffered losses from AAA-ratings created by financial engineering (which creates apparently risk-free assets from high-risk collateral) which requires less capital as per Basel II. Lending to AA rated sovereigns has a risk-weight of zero, thus leading to lending to governments and the next crisis. Johan Norberg argues that the regulations (Basel III among others) have actually led to excessive lending to risky governments (see European sovereign-debt crisis) and that the ECB is lending even more as a solution.

Haya-Azi was immediately followed by the states of Arma-Shupriya (1300–1190 BC), Nairi (1400–1000 BC) and Urartu (860–590 BC), which successively established their sovereignty over the Armenian Highland. . Each of the above mentioned nations and tribes participated in the ethnogenesis of the Armenian people. Under Ashurbanipal (669–627 BC), the Assyrian Empire reached the Caucasus Mountains (modern Armenia, Georgia, and Azerbaijan).
questions_en: When did Nairi rule?

context_en: In recent years it has become common for many AC stations, especially soft AC stations, to play primarily or exclusively Christmas music during the Christmas season in November and December. context_en: A comprehensive school is a state school which does not offer intake on the basis of academic achievement or merit. This is in contrast to the selective school system, where admission is restricted based on selection criteria. The term is usually used in relation to England and Wales, where comprehensive schools were introduced on an experimental basis in the 1940s and became more widespread from 1965. Around 90% of British secondary school students now attend comprehensive schools. They broadly correspond to public high school in the United States and Canada and the German Gesamtschule. [citation needed].
questions_en: What kind of school systems use academic success to judge admissions?

context_en: Beyoncé's first solo recording was a feature on Jay Z's "'03 Bonnie and Clyde" which was released in October 2002, which peaked at number four on the U.K. Billboard Hot 100 chart. Her first solo album In Love was released on June 24, 2003, after Michelle Williams and Kelly Rowland released their solo efforts. The album sold 317,000 copies in its first week, debuting atop the Billboard 200, and has since sold 11 million copies worldwide. The album's lead single, "Crazy in Love", featuring Jay Z, became Beyoncé's first number-one single as a solo artist. The single "Baby Boy" also reached number one, and the singles, "Me, Me and Me" and "Naughty Girl", both reached the top five. The album earned Beyoncé a record-tying five awards at the 46th Annual Grammy Awards; Best Contemporary R&B Album, Best Female R&B Vocal Performance for "Dangerously in Love 2", Best R&B Song and Best R&B Song for "Crazy". context_en: In Canada, the term "football" may refer to Canadian football and American football collectively, or to the sport specifically, depending on the context. The two games share origins and are closely related but there are significant differences. Specifically, Canadian football has 12 players on the field per team instead of 11; the field is approximately 10 yards across, and the end-zones are 10 yards longer than the end zone; And a team has only three downs for 10 yards, resulting in less aggressive rushing than in the American game. In the Canadian game all players on the defending team, when starting downs, must be at least 1 yard from the line of scrimmage. (There is a similar "neutral zone" in American sports, but it is only the length of a football.
questions_en: How many downs does a team have ten yards in Canadian football?

context_en: Greece has lagged behind its EU partners in terms of internet usage, with the shutdown accelerating in recent years. The percentage of households with access to the Internet ranged from 23% to 56% between 2006 and 2013 (compared to the EU average of 49% and 79%, respectively). At the same time, the proportion of households with a broadband connection has increased significantly, from 4% in 2006 to 55% in 2013 (compared to the EU average of 30% and 76%). However, Greece also has the EU's third highest percentage of people who have never used the Internet: 36% in 2013, down from 65% in 2006 (compared to the EU average of 21% and 42%).
questions_en: What percentage of people in Greece had never used the Internet as of 2013?

context_en: In breeding circles, a male canine is known as a dog, while a female is called a bitch (Middle English bicc, from Old English bicce, ultimately from Old Norse bichka). A group of offspring is a litter. The father of a litter is called the sire, and the mother is called the dam. The offspring, in general, are called puppies or pups, from the French Popeye, until they are about a year old. The old English word helps speed up the birth process.
questions_en: What is the French word that "puppy" comes from?

context_en: आर्मेनियाई नरसंहार ने व्यापक प्रवासन का कारण बना दिया जिससे दुनिया के विभिन्न देशों में आर्मेनियों के निपटारे का नेतृत्व किया। आर्मेनियाई अपनी परंपराओं में रखे और कुछ डायस्पोरन अपने संगीत के साथ प्रसिद्धि के लिए गुलाब। संयुक्त राज्य अमेरिका के नरसंहार आर्मेनियाई समुदाय में, तथाकथित "केईएफ" शैली अर्मेनियाई नृत्य संगीत, आर्मेनियाई और मध्य पूर्वी लोक उपकरणों (अक्सर विद्युतीकृत / प्रवर्धित) और कुछ पश्चिमी उपकरणों का उपयोग करके लोकप्रिय था। इस शैली ने पश्चिमी आर्मेनिया के लोक गीतों और नृत्य को संरक्षित किया, और कई कलाकारों ने तुर्की और अन्य मध्य पूर्वी देशों के समकालीन लोकप्रिय गीतों को भी खेला, जिनसे आर्मेनियन उत्सर्जित हुए। रिचर्ड हैगोपियन शायद पारंपरिक "केएफ" शैली का सबसे प्रसिद्ध कलाकार है और वोस्किबियन बैंड 40 के दशक में "केएफ संगीत" की अपनी शैली को विकसित करने के लिए 40 के दशक में उल्लेखनीय था, जो उस समय के लोकप्रिय अमेरिकी बड़े बैंड जैज़ से काफी प्रभावित था। बाद में, मध्य पूर्वी आर्मेनियाई डायस्पोरा से निकलकर महाद्वीपीय यूरोपीय (विशेष रूप से फ्रेंच) पॉप संगीत से प्रभावित, आर्मेनियाई पॉप संगीत शैली 60 के दशक में प्रसिद्धि के लिए बढ़ी और 70 के दशक जैसे कलाकारों के साथ कलाकारों और अर्मेनियाई डायस्पोरा और आर्मेनिया के लिए प्रदर्शन कर रहे हैं।। सिराशो जैसे कलाकारों के साथ, आज के मनोरंजन उद्योग में आर्मेनियाई लोक संगीत के साथ संयुक्त पॉप संगीत का प्रदर्शन। शास्त्रीय या अंतरराष्ट्रीय संगीत सर्कल में प्रसिद्धि के लिए गुलाब के अन्य आर्मेनियाई डायस्पोरन्स विश्व प्रसिद्ध फ्रांसीसी-आर्मेनियाई गायक और संगीतकार चार्ल्स अज़नावोर, पियानोवादक साहन आर्ज़ुनी, प्रमुख ओपेरा सोप्रानोस जैसे हसमिक पापियन और हाल ही में इसाबेल बेर्यमेरियन और अन्ना कासियन हैं। कुछ आर्मेनियाई लोग गैर-आर्मेनियाई धुनों जैसे कि भारी धातु बैंड प्रणाली जैसे नीचे की ओर गाते हैं (जो फिर भी पारंपरिक आर्मेनियाई वाद्ययंत्र और स्टाइलिंग को उनके गीतों में शामिल करते हैं) या पॉप स्टार चेर। रूबेन हाकोबायन (रूबेन ससुंस्सी) एक अच्छी तरह से मान्यता प्राप्त आर्मेनियाई नृवंशविज्ञान और देशभक्ति लोक गायक हैं जिन्होंने अर्मेनियाई लोक संगीत और असाधारण प्रतिभा के प्रति अपनी भक्ति के कारण व्यापक राष्ट्रीय मान्यता प्राप्त की है। आर्मेनियाई डायस्पोरा में, आर्मेनियाई क्रांतिकारी गीत युवाओं के साथ लोकप्रिय हैं। [उद्धरण वांछित] ये गीत आर्मेनियाई देशभक्ति को प्रोत्साहित करते हैं और आम तौर पर अर्मेनियाई इतिहास और राष्ट्रीय नायकों के बारे में होते हैं।

context_en: With advances in medicinal chemistry, most modern antibacterials are semisynthetic modifications of various natural compounds. For example, beta-lactam antibiotics, including penicillins (produced by fungi in the genus Penicillium), cephalosporins, and carbapenems. The compounds that are still isolated from living organisms are aminoglycosides, while other antibacterials—for example, sulfonamides, quinolones, and oxazolidinones—are produced only by chemical synthesis. Many antibacterial compounds are relatively small molecules with molecular weights of less than 2000 atomic mass units. [citation needed].
questions_en: Apart from semisynthetic modification, what advances in medicinal chemistry regarding antibacterials?

context_en: In Theravada Buddhism there can be no divine salvation or forgiveness for one's karma, as this is a completely illegitimate process that is part of the makeup of the universe. [citation needed] In Mahayana Buddhism, some Mahayana sutra texts (such as the Lotus Sutra, the Igulimalisha Sutra and the Mahina Mahapirinirvana Sutra) claim that recitation or merely hearing of their texts can eliminate great swathes of negative karma. Some forms of Buddhism (for example, Vajrayana) view the recitation of mantras as a means of cutting past negative karma. The Japanese Pure Land teacher Genshin taught that Amitabha has the power to destroy the karma that would otherwise bind one in Saseshara.
questions_en: According to Gnesin, what has the power to destroy karma?

Most of the interments in the abbey are crucifixed remains, but some burials still occur – Francis Challen, wife of the Rev. context_en: Nanjing, for more than a thousand years one of the country's most important cities, is recognized as one of the four great ancient capitals of China, and was the world's largest city for hundreds of years, enjoying peace and prosperity. Took and enjoyed wars and disasters. Nanjing served as the capital of Eastern Wu, one of the three major states in the Three Kingdoms period (211–280); Eastern Jin and each of the Southern dynasties (Liu Song, Southern Qi, Liang, and Chen), which ended in 317. -ruled southern China continuously from 589; the Southern Tang, one of the Ten Kingdoms (937–76); the Ming dynasty, for the first time, ruled all of China (1368–1421); and during the Chinese Civil War Republic of China before the flight to Taiwan (1927–37, 1945–49). The city also served as the seat of the rebellious Taiping Heavenly Kingdom (1851–64) and the Japanese puppet regime of Wang Jingwei (1940–45) during the Second Sino-Japanese War, and endured atrocities in both conflicts, including the Nanjing Massacre. It has served as the capital city of Jiangsu Province since the founding of China, and is still the nominal capital of the Republic of China housing many of its important heritage sites, including the Presidential Palace and the Sun Yat-sen Mausoleum. Nanjing is famous for human historical landscapes, mountains and waters such as Fujimiao, Ming Palace, Chatin Palace, porcelain tower, drum tower, stone city, city wall, Qianhui River, Xuanwu Lake and purple mountain. Main cultural facilities include the Nanjing Library, the Nanjing Museum and the Art Museum.
questions_en: How many great ancient capitals does China have?

context_en: Just over 200 kilometers (120 mi) north and 130 kilometers (81 mi) east to west, Swaziland is one of the smallest countries in Africa. Despite its size, however, its climate and topography are diverse, ranging from a cool and mountainous highveld to the hot and dry lowveld. The population is predominantly ethnic Swazis whose language is Siswati. They established their kingdom under the leadership of Ngwane III in the mid-18th century; the current boundaries were drawn in 1881. After the Anglo-Boer War, Swaziland was a British protectorate from 1903 to 1967. It gained its independence on 6 September 1968.

context_en: In separate testimony to the Financial Crisis Inquiry Commission, executives of Clayton Holdings—the largest residential loan due diligence and securitization monitoring company in the United States and Europe—testified that Clayton reviewed more than 900,000 mortgages issued from January 2006 to June 2007. revealed that barely 54% of the loans met the underwriting standards of their originators. context_en: The study of genocide focuses primarily towards the legal aspect of the term. By formally recognizing the act of genocide as a crime, it involves sustained prosecution that not only begins with viewing genocide as having any moral standing but can also lead to a legal liability within international relations. When genocide is viewed in a general aspect it is seen as the deliberate killing of a certain group. Yet genocide is seen to avoid the process of trial and prosecution due to the fact that genocide is more often than not committed by authorities in power of a state or territory. Before the term genocide was coined in 1648, the Peace of Westphalia was established to protect ethnic, national, racial, and in some cases religious groups. During the 19th century there was a need for humanitarian intervention due to the fact of conflict and justification of certain actions performed by the military.
questions_en: In what year was the Peace of Westphalia signed?

context_en: In contrast to previous wars, many middle and small powers in Europe tried to move away from the escalating conflict, even if they had interests in the conflict or were involved, like Denmark–Norway. The Dutch Republic, a longtime British ally, maintained its neutrality, fearing the odds against Britain and Prussia, even going so far as to fight the Great Powers of Europe in an attempt to prevent British dominance in India. Naples, Sicily, and Savoy, although siding with the Franco-Spanish party, refused to join the coalition under fear of British power. The taxation required for the war caused considerable hardship to the Russian people, added to the taxation of salt and wine initiated by Empress Elizabeth in 1759 to finance her addition to the Winter Palace. Like Sweden, Russia concluded a separate peace with Prussia.
questions_en: How did the war affect the Russian population?
answers_en: The taxation required for the war caused considerable hardship to the Russian people.

context_en: In an October 2004 case, Telewiza Polska USA, Inc. v. EchoStar Satellite, No. 02 C 3293, 65 Fed. R Avid. serve. 673 (N.D. Ill. context_en: IndiMac loans are often made without verification of the borrower's income or assets, and to borrowers with poor credit histories. context_en: From September 1823 to 1826 Chopin attended the Warsaw Lyceum, where he received organ lessons from the Czech composer Wilhelm Wurfel during his first year. [n3] During this period he continued to write and to give recitals in concerts and salons in Warsaw. He was engaged by the inventors of a mechanical organ, the "Eolomelodikon", and in May 1825 on this instrument he performed his own improvisations and part of a concerto by Moscheles. The success of this concert led to an invitation from Tsar Alexander I, who was visiting Warsaw, to perform a similar citation on the first instrument; the tsar presented him with a diamond ring. At the subsequent Éolomelodikon concert on 10 June 1825, Chopin performed his Rondo Op. It was the first of his works to be published commercially and earned him his first mention in the foreign press, when the Leipzig Allgemeine Musikalische Zeitung praised its "wealth of musical ideas".

context_en: Armenian literature dates back to 400 AD, when Mesop Mashtots invented the first Armenian alphabet. This period is often seen as the Golden Age of Armenian literature. Early Armenian literature was written by the "Father of Armenian History", Moses of Korin, who wrote a history of Armenia. The book covers the time-frame from the formation of the Armenian people to the fifth century AD. There is a great literary movement in the nineteenth century which was to give rise to modern Armenian literature. This period of time, during which Armenian culture flourished, is known as the Revival Period (Zartanki Sherchan). The revivalist writers of Constantinople and Tiflis, almost identical to the Romantics of Europe, were interested in encouraging Armenian nationalism. Most of them adopted newly created Eastern or Western forms of the Armenian language, depending on the target audience, and preferred them over Classical Armenian (Grabar). This period ended after the Hamidian Genocide, when the Armenians experienced turbulent times. As the 1920s and the Armenian history of the genocide became more openly discussed, writers such as Periyar Sevak, Gevork Emin, Silva Kaputikyan and Hovhannes Shiraz began a new era of literature.

context_en: Nanjing has a humid subtropical climate (Köppen Cfa) and is under the influence of the East Asian monsoon. The four seasons are distinct, with moist conditions seen throughout the year, a very hot and muggy summer, a cold, moist winter, and a fair length of fall in the middle, spring and autumn. Along with Chongqing and Wuhan, Nanjing is traditionally known as one of the "Three Fernancial Cities" along the Yangtze River (长江流域三大火炉) for its perennially high temperatures in summer. However, mid-June to late July is the plum blossom blooming season marked by Meiyu (the rainy season of East Asia; literally "plum rain"), during which the city experiences a period of light rain in the form of humidity. Typhoons are uncommon but possible in the late stages of summer and early part of autumn. The annual average temperature is about 15. 46 °C (59.8 °F), with a monthly 24-hour average temperature ranging from 2. 4 °C (36.3° F) in January to 27.8 °C (82.0° F) in July. Extremes since 1951 have occurred at -14. 0 °C (7 °F) to 40 on 6 January 1955. 7 °C (105 °F) on 22 August 1959. The average rainfall is 115 days a year, and the average annual rainfall is 1,062 millimeters (42 in). With monthly percent possible sunshine ranging from 37 percent in March to 52 percent in August, the city receives 1,983 hours of bright sunshine annually.

context_en: Japan: The event was held in Nagano, which hosted the 1998 Winter Olympics, on 26 April. Also the threat of disruption from violent protests. Parts of the ZENKō-JI Temple main building (ZENKō-JI Hondō), renovated in 1707 and one of the National Treasures of Japan, were then vandalized with spray paint. A new starting point, previously the site of a municipal building and now a parking lot, was chosen by the city. An event planned to be held at the Minami Nagano Sports Park after the torch relay was canceled out of concern about disruptions caused by protesters protesting against China's recent crackdown on Tibet. Thousands of riot police were mobilized to protect the torch along its route. The show of force kept most protesters in check, but slogans shouted by pro-China or pro-Tibet protesters, Japanese nationalists and human rights organizations filled the air. Five men were arrested and four were injured amid scenes of major violence. The torch route was packed with mostly peaceful protesters. Parks were not allowed at the parking lot where the relay started. Zenkozi monks hold a prayer ceremony for the victims of recent events in Tibet. More than 100 police officers rushed in with torches and riot police lined the streets while three helicopters flew overhead. Only two Chinese guards were allowed to accompany the torch due to Japan's concern over the treatment of protesters in previous relays. "The two spent an unhappy winter in Majorca (from 8 November 1838 to 13 February 1839), where, with the two children of Sands, , he had traveled in the hope of improving the health of Chopin and Sand's 15-year-old son Maurice, and also to escape threats from Sand's former lover Félicien Mallefil after discovering that the couple was not married. context_en: From the beginning of the 16th century, both Western Armenia and Eastern Armenia fell under Iranian Persian rule. Due to the century-long Turco-Iranian geopolitical rivalry that would last across Western Asia, significant parts of the region were often contested between the two rival empires. From the mid-16th century with the Peace of Amasya, and decisively from the first half of the 17th century with the Treaty of Zubab until the first half of the 19th century, Eastern Armenia was successively ruled by the Iranian Safavid, Affarid and Qajar empires. While Western Armenia remained under Ottoman rule. In the late 1820s, parts of historical Armenia under Iranian control centered on Iran and Lake Sevan (Eastern Armenia) were incorporated into the Russian Empire following Iran's forced ceding of power following its losses in the Russo-Persian War ( 1826--1828) and the subsequent Treaty of Turkmenchay. Western Armenia, however, remained in Ottoman hands.

context_en: From September 1823 to 1826 Chopin attended the Warsaw Lyceum, where he received organ lessons from the Czech composer Wilhelm Wurfel during his first year. In the autumn of 1826 he began a three-year course under the Silesian composer Józef Elsner at the Warsaw Conservatory, studying music theory, bass and composition. [n3] During this period he continued to write and to give recitals in concerts and salons in Warsaw. He was engaged by the inventors of a mechanical organ, the "Eolomelodikon", and in May 1825 on this instrument he performed his own improvisations and part of a concerto by Moscheles. The success of this concert led to an invitation from Tsar Alexander I, who was visiting Warsaw, to perform a similar citation on the first instrument; the tsar presented him with a diamond ring. At the subsequent Éolomelodikon concert on 10 June 1825, Chopin performed his Rondo Op. It was the first of his works to be published commercially and earned him his first mention in the foreign press, when the Leipzig Allgemeine Musikalische Zeitung praised its "wealth of musical ideas".

context_en: Montana Territory was created on April 26, 1864, when U. Organic Act passed. Schools began to be officially constructed in the area as families began to settle in the area. The first schools were subscription schools usually held in the teacher's home. The first formal school on record was at Fort Owen in the Bitterroot Valley in 1862. The students were Indian children and children of Fort Owen employees. The first school term started in early winter and lasted only until 28 February. Classes were taught by Shri. Robinson. Another early subscription school was started by Thomas Dimsdale in Virginia City in 1863. Students at this school were charged $1. 75 per week. The Montana Territorial Legislative Assembly had its inaugural meeting in 1864. The first legislature authorized counties to levy taxes for schools, which set the foundation for public schooling. Madison County was the first to take advantage of the newly authorized taxes and in 1886 the FHE First Public School was formed in Virginia City. The first school year was scheduled to begin in January 1866, but severe weather postponed its opening until March. The first school year ran through the summer and did not end until August 17. One of the first teachers at the school was Sarah Raymond. She was a 25-year-old woman who traveled to Virginia City via wagon train in 1865. To become a certified teacher, Raymond took a test in his home and paid a $6 fee in gold dust to receive a teaching certificate. With the help of an assistant teacher, Smt. Farley was responsible for teaching 50 to 60 students each day out of the 81 students enrolled at the Raymond School. Sarah Raymond was paid at the rate of $125 per month, and Mrs. Foley was paid $75 per month. There were no textbooks in the school. In their place was an assortment of books brought by various immigrants. Sarah dropped out the following year, but would later become Madison County Superintendent.

context_en: Biodiversity, a contraction of "biological diversity", generally refers to the diversity and variability of life on Earth. One of the most widely used definitions defines it in terms of variability within species, between species, and between ecosystems. It is a measure of the diversity of organisms present in different ecosystems. It may refer to genetic variation, ecosystem variation, or species variation (number of species) within a region, biome, or planet. Terrestrial biodiversity tends to be greater near the equator, which appears to be a result of the warmer climate and higher primary productivity. Biodiversity is not distributed evenly on Earth. It is the richest in the tropics. Marine biodiversity is highest along the coasts in the western Pacific, where sea surface temperatures are highest and in mid-latitude bands of all oceans. There are latitudinal gradients in species diversity. Biodiversity is generally clustered in hotspots, and has been increasing through time, but will likely slow in the future.

context_en: All of Chopin's compositions involve piano. Most are for solo piano, although he also wrote two piano concertos, some chamber pieces, and some ballads for polish. Chopin invented the concept of the instrumental ballad. His major piano works also include Mazurkas, Waltzes, Nocturnes, Polonaises, Études, Impromptus, Scherzos, Predudes and Sonatas, some published only after his death. Influences on his creative style include Polish folk music, the classical tradition of J. Bach, Mozart and Schubert, all of whose music he admired, as well as the Paris Salon where he was a frequent guest. Their innovations in style, musical form, and harmony, and their association with nationalism, were influential throughout and after the late Romantic period.

context_en: In the spring of 1834, Chopin attended the Lower Rhenish Music Festival at Aix-la-Chapelle with Hiller, and it was there that Chopin met Felix Mendelssohn. After the festival, the trio visited Düsseldorf, where Mendelssohn was appointed music director. He spent what Mendelssohn described as "a very agreeable day", playing and discussing music at his piano, and meeting Friedrich Wilhelm Schadow, director of the Academy of Art, and some of his distinguished pupils such as Low, Bendmann, Met Hildebrand and Sohn. In 1835 Chopin went to Carlsbad, where he spent time with his parents; the last time he would see them. On his way back to Paris, he met old friends from Warsaw, the Wodzińskis. He introduced his daughter Maria to Poland five years ago, when she was eleven. This meeting led him to stay for two weeks in Dresden, when he had previously intended to return to Paris via Leipzig. The composer's portrait of a sixteen-year-old girl, along with Delacroix's, are regarded as Chopin's best parallels. In October he finally reached Leipzig, where he met Schumann, Clara Wieck and Felix Mendelssohn, who performed for him his own oratorio St. Paul, and who considered him "an ideal musician". In July 1836 Chopin traveled with the Wodziński family to Marienbad and Dresden, and in September he proposed to Maria, whose mother Countess Wodzińska approved in principle. Chopin moved to Leipzig, where he presented Schumann with his G minor Ballade. At the end of 1836 he sent Maria an album in which her sister Ludwika had inscribed seven of his songs, and his 1835 Nocturne in C-sharp minor, Op. 27, no. The anodyne thank you he received from Maria proved to be the last letter he had.

context_en: Before the beginning of the 20th century, treatments for infections were primarily based on medicinal folklore. Mixtures with antimicrobial properties that were used in the treatment of infections were described 2000 years ago. Many ancient cultures, including the ancient Egyptians and ancient Greeks, used specially selected molds and plant materials and extracted extracts to treat infections. More recent observations made in the laboratory of antibiosis among microorganisms initiated the discovery of natural antibacterials produced by microorganisms. Louis Pasteur observed, "If we could interfere with the rivalry observed between certain bacteria, it would perhaps offer the greatest hopes for therapeutics". The term 'antibiosis', meaning "against life", was introduced by the French bacteriologist Jean Paul Villemin as a descriptive name for the phenomenon exhibited by these early antibacterial drugs. Louis Pasteur and Robert Koch observed that antibiosis was first described in bacteria in 1877, when an airborne bacillus could inhibit the growth of Bacillus anthracis. These drugs were later named antibiotics by Selman Waksman, an American microbiologist in 1942. The science and development of antibacterials as synthetic antibiotic chemotherapy began in Germany with Paul Ehrlich in the late 1880s. Ehrlich noted that some dyes would color human, animal, or bacterial cells, while others did not. He then proposed the idea that it might be possible to create chemicals that would act as a selective drug that would bind and kill the bacteria without harming the human host. After screening hundreds of dyes against different organisms, in 1907, he discovered a medicinally useful drug, the synthetic antibacterial salvarsan now called arsphenamine.
questions_en: What methods did people use to treat infections before antibiotics?

context_en: To put it another way, a thing or person is often seen as having a "defined essence" or "core identity" that is immutable, and describes what the thing or person really is. In this way of thinking, things and people are seen as fundamentally identical over time, with any changes being qualitative and secondary to their core identity (e. "Mark's hair has turned gray because he He's grown older, but he's still the same person"). But in Whitehead's cosmology, the only fundamentally existing things are separate "occasions of experience" that overlap each other in time and space, and jointly make up an enduring person or thing. On the other hand, common thinking often treats "the essence of something" or "a person's identity/core" as the most important or salient characteristics of that person or thing at a given time. One of its essence is generalization. Identities don't define people, people define identities. Everything changes from moment to moment, and to think of anything as having a "permanent essence" misses the fact that "all things flow", although this is often a useful way of speaking.

context_en: In higher organisms (like people), these two modes of perception combine in what Whitehead terms "symbolic reference", linking appearance with reason in a process that is so automatic that both people and animals are able to avoid it. There is difficulty. By way of illustration, Whitehead uses the example of a person's encounter with a chair. An ordinary person looks up, sees a colorful shape, and immediately assumes it is a chair. However, an artist, Whitehead believes, "might not jump to the notion of a chair", but instead might stop at "the mere contemplation of a beautiful color and the contemplation of a beautiful shape." There is no reaction; Most people place objects into categories by habit and instinct, without even thinking about it. Besides, animals do the same thing. Using the same example, Whitehead explains that a dog "will act immediately on the hypothesis of a chair and thus will have jumped through to use it." Thus symbolic reference is a fusion of pure emotion perceptions on the one hand and On the other side are causal relations, and it is precisely the causal relations that dominate the more basic mentality (as the dog shows), while it is the sense perceptions that point to a higher grade mentality (as the artist shows).
