context_en: Political anthropology is concerned with the structure of political systems, viewed from the basis of the structure of society. While political anthropology developed as a discipline primarily concerned with politics in stateless societies, a new development began from the 1960s, and is still manifesting: anthropologists increasingly turn to "complex" social settings to study In which the presence of states, bureaucracies, and markets entered both ethnographic accounts and analyzes of local events. The turn towards complex societies meant that political issues were addressed at two main levels. At first, anthropologists continued to study political organization and political phenomena that lay outside the state-regulated sphere (in patron-client relationships or tribal political organization). Second, anthropologists gradually began to develop a disciplinary concern with states and their institutions (and with the relationship between formal and informal political institutions). An anthropology of the state developed, and today it is the most promising field. Geertz' comparative work on "Negara", the Balinese state, is an early, well-known example.

context_en: In 1977, Gaddafi dissolved the republic and created a new socialist state, the Jamahiriya ("people's state"). A particularly hostile relationship developed with the United States and the United Kingdom, resulting in the 1986 U.N. The bombing of Libya and UN-imposed economic sanctions. Rejecting his previous ideological commitments, from 1999 onwards Gaddafi encouraged economic privatization and sought rapprochement with Western countries, while also embracing Pan-Africanism and helping to establish the African Union. context_en: Two major extant branches of Buddhism are generally recognized by scholars: Theravada ("The School of the Elders") and Mahayana ("The Great Whack"). Vajrayana, a body of teachings attributed to the Indian Siddhas, can be seen as a third branch or simply a part of the Mahayana. Theravada has a wide following in Sri Lanka and Southeast Asia. Mahayana, which includes the Pure Land, Zen, Nichiren Buddhism, Shingon, and Tiannai (Tendai) traditions, is found throughout East Asia. Tibetan Buddhism, which preserves the Vajrayana teachings of eighth-century India, is practiced in the Himalayas, Mongolia, and the surrounding areas of Kalmykia. Buddhists number between an estimated 488 million [web 1] and 535 million, making it one of the world's major religions.

context_en: Several molecular mechanisms of antibacterial resistance exist. Intrinsic antibacterial resistance may be part of the genetic makeup of bacterial strains. For example, an antibiotic target may be absent from the bacterial genome. Acquired resistance results from a mutation in the bacterial chromosome or the acquisition of extra chromosomal DNA. Antibacterial-producing bacteria have evolved resistance mechanisms that have been shown to be similar, and have been transferred to antibacterial-resistant strains. The spread of antibacterial resistance often occurs through vertical transmission of mutations during evolution and by genetic recombination of DNA by horizontal genetic exchange. For example, antibacterial resistance genes can be exchanged through these resistance genes between different bacterial strains or species. Plasmids that carry several different resistance genes can confer multiple antibacterial resistance. Cross-resistance to multiple antibacterials can also occur when a resistance mechanism encoded by a single gene confers resistance to more than one antibacterial compound.
questions_en: What can be absent from the bacterial genome?

context_en: In Whitehead's view, then, concepts such as "quality", "matter", and "form" are problematic. After all, people change all the time, if only because they are older than the second and have had some more experiences. These occasions of experience are logically distinct, but progressively linked in what Whitehead calls a "society" of events. context_en: Formal discipline is administered by the elders of the congregation. Business dealings may continue. Witnesses are taught that avoiding social and spiritual interactions with disfellowshipped individuals keeps the congregation free from immoral influences and that "losing valuable fellowship with loved ones can help [the shunned individual] 'come to his senses' , 'See the seriousness of his wrongness, and take steps to return to Jehovah.' The practice of rocking may also serve to deter other members from disloyal behavior. Members who disassociate (formally resign) are described as wicked in Watch Tower Society literature and are even more appalled. Disfellowshipped persons may eventually be reinstated to the congregation if repentant by the elders in the congregation in which the disfellowshipment was made. Reparation is a shorter form of discipline formally given by a judicial committee to a baptized person who is considered to have repented of serious sin; the repentant person temporarily loses specific privileges of service, but has no access to social or spiritual fellowship. There is no restriction. Marking, social but not spiritual fellowship, is practiced if a baptized member commits serious, but not serious, sin in what is perceived as a violation of Biblical principles. [Note 4].

context_en: A dense wave of smoke began to spread over central and eastern parts of China on 2 December 2013, covering a distance of about 1,200 kilometers (750 mi), including Tianjin, Hebei, Shandong, Jiangsu, Anhui, Shanghai and Zhejiang. The lack of cold airflow, combined with slow-moving air masses carrying industrial emissions, caused airborne pollutants to accumulate to form a thick layer of smog over the area. Heavy smoke heavily polluted central and southern Jiangsu province, especially in and around Nanjing, for five straight days with "severely polluted" and "heavily polluted" for nine. On December 3, 2013, PM2 levels. The mean average concentration averaged over 943 micrograms per cubic metre, falling to 338 micrograms per cubic meter on 4 December 2013. Between 3:00 a.m., December 3, and 2:00 a.m., December 4 local time, several expressways from Nanjing to other Jiangsu cities were closed, grounding dozens of passenger buses at the Zhongyangmen bus station. From December 5 to 6, Nanjing issued a red alert for air pollution and closed all kindergarten through middle schools. Children's hospital outpatient services increased by 33 percent; common incidences of bronchitis, pneumonia, upper respiratory tract infections increased significantly. The smog ended on 12 December. Officials blamed the dense pollution on lack of air, automobile exhaust emissions under low air pressure, and the lack of coal-powered district heating systems in the northern China region. The prevailing winds blew low-hanging air masses of factory emissions (mostly SO2) toward the east coast of China.

context_en: Nanjing (listen; Chinese: 南京, "Southern Capital") is a city located in the heartland of the lower Yangtze River region in China, which has long been a major center of culture, education, research, politics, economy, transportation networks, and tourism. . It is the largest city in Jiangsu province of the People's Republic of China and the second largest city in East China, with a total population of 8,216,100, and is de jure the capital of the Republic of China, having lost the mainland during the civil war. The city that bears its name, the "Southern Capital", has a prominent place in Chinese history and culture, having served as the capitals of various Chinese dynasties, empires, and republican governments from the 3rd century AD to 1949. Before the advent of pinyin romanization, the city name of Nanjing was written as Nanking or Nanqin. Nanjing has several other names, and some historical names are now used as the names of districts of the city, and among them is the name Jiangning (江寧), the former character of which is part of Jiang (江, river), the former name Jiangsu and The latter character Ning (寧, simplified form 宁, peace) is a diminutive of Nanjing. When the state capital is, for example, the ROC, Jing (京) is adopted as the abbreviation for Nanjing. Although a city located in the southern part of China became the Chinese national capital as early as the Jin Dynasty, the name Nanjing was changed to designate the city a thousand years later in the Ming Dynasty. context_en: By 1763, the war in Central Europe was essentially a stalemate. Frederick kept Silesia and much of Saxony, but not the latter's capital, Dresden. context_en: After being lit at the birthplace of the Olympic Games in Olympia, Greece, on March 24, the torch traveled to the Panathinaiko Stadium in Athens, and then to Beijing, arriving on March 31. From Beijing, the torch was following a route passing through six continents. The torch has visited cities along the Silk Road, symbolizing the ancient links between China and the rest of the world. The relay also included a climb with the flame to the top of Mount Everest on the border between Nepal and Tibet, China, which was specially closed for the event.

context_en: In the late summer he was invited by Jane Stirling to visit Scotland, where he stayed at Calder House near Edinburgh and Johnstone Castle in Renfrewshire, both owned by members of Stirling's family. She clearly had the notion of going beyond friendship, and Chopin was obliged to make it clear that this could not be so. He wrote to Grzymała at this time "My Scottish women are kind, but such bores", and responding to a rumor about his involvement, replied that he was "closer to the grave than the impotent bed. "He gave a public concert in Glasgow on 27 September, and another in Edinburgh at the Hopetoun Rooms on Queen Street (now Erskine House) on 4 October. In late October 1848, while living at 10 Warriston Crescent in Edinburgh with the Polish physician Adam Łyszczyński, he wrote his last will and testament—"a kind disposition to be made of my belongings in the future, if I should be left dead anywhere". , he wrote to Grzymała.
